66558,lobbying.ie/return/66558/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:36,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Matters involving public funds,Finance,IFA 2021 Budget Submission - Expenditure Measures to Support Farm Enterprises,"Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Alan Dillon|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Dara Calleary|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Lisa Chambers|Senator|Seanad::Seán Canney|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Ciaran Cannon|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Hildegarde Naughton|Super Junior Minister|Department of Climate Action, Communication Networks and Transport::Noel Grealish|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Seán Kyne|Senator|Seanad::Ollie Crowe|Senator|Seanad::Éamon Ó Cuív|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Pauline O'Reilly|Senator|Seanad::Mairéad Farrell|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Rose Conway-Walsh|Senator|Seanad::Michael Creed|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Colm Burke|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Pádraig O'Sullivan|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::James O'Connor|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Holly Cairns|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Christopher O'Sullivan|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Norma Foley|Minister|Department of Education and Skills::Brendan Griffin|Minister of State|Department of Transport, Tourism and Sport::Danny Healy-Rae|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Healy-Rae|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Pa Daly|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Robert Troy|Minister of State|Department of Enterprise, Trade and Employment::Robert Troy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Sorca Clarke|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Carol Nolan|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Cathal Berry|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Sean Fleming|Minister of State|Department of Finance::Brian Stanley|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Denis Naughten|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Claire Kerrane|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paschal Donohoe|Minister|Department of Finance::Michael McGrath|Minister|Department of Public Expenditure and Reform::Patrick O'Donovan|Minister of State|The Office of Public Works::Pearse Doherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Aisling Dolan|Senator|Seanad::Martin Heydon|Minister of State|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Frank Feighan|Minister of State|Department of Health::Marc MacSharry|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Kenny|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Marian Harkin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Heather Humphreys|Minister|Department of Arts, Heritage and the Gaeltacht::Leo Varadkar|Minister|Department of Defence::Simon Harris|Minister|Department of Health::Niamh Smyth|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Pauline Tully|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe O'Reilly|Senator|Seanad::Brendan Smith|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Robbie Gallagher|Senator|Seanad::Joe McHugh|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Garrett Ahern|Senator|Seanad::Joe Carey|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Alan Kelly|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Mattie McGrath|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Conway|Senator|Seanad::Michael McNamara|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Cathal Crowe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Violet Anne Wynne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Timmy Dooley|Senator|Seanad::Róisín Garvey|Senator|Seanad::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Lowry|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Bernard Durkan|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Kieran O'Donnell|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Mary Butler|Minister of State|Department of Health::Richard O'Donoghue|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Moynihan|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Fergus O'Dowd|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament::Pippa Hackett|Super Junior Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Helen McEntee|Minister|Department of Justice and Equality::Damien English|Minister of State|Department of Housing, Planning and Local Government::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament","Farm Schemes - that the total annual CAP payment plus the national co-financing must amount to €2bn per annum, from the current level of €1.8bn from when the new CAP starts.::Suckler Cow::- Suckler farmers need a targeted payment of €300 per cow, facilitated by a combination of CAP and national funding.::- For 2020, a total of 27,000 suckler farmers have applied for the BEEP-S scheme, with up to 600,000 cows.  At the payment rates of €90 on the first 10 cows and €80 on the remainder, the funding costs of this scheme will be up to €52m in 2020, as opposed to the €35m allocated in 2019. This means this scheme will need a budget injection of an additional €17m for 2020.::- For 2021, the IFA is proposing the BDGP is renewed and simplified with funding increased from €45m to €90m pa.::- This would provide total funding of €142m pa for sucklers (BDGP €90m and BEEP-S €52m) and enable payment rates of €290 per cow on the first 10 cows and €250 per cow on the remainder.::- An enhanced environmental scheme must be introduced to acknowledge the carbon sink provided by agriculture and to support vulnerable sectors like sucklers.::Sheep Welfare Scheme - that a targeted payment of €30 per ewe through a combination of CAP transition and national funding is needed for sheep farmers.  Across the national flock of 2.57 million breeding ewes, this would require total funding of €77m pa.::Agri-Environment Schemes - that the GLAS scheme must be reopened for all farmers who are currently denied entry.  This includes new entrants since 2015 as well as the 2,000 farmers who were in AEO's whose contracts finished in 2018.::- For the 36,000 farmers finishing GLAS on December 31st 2020 their plans must be extended for up to 2 years or for the period of CAP transition, and all payment rates must be maintained.::- €232m funding allocation is required for all environmental and locally led schemes, including GLAS, the Burren, Hen Harrier and Organic Schemes.::Areas of Natural Constraints (ANCs) - that funding for the ANCs must be increased by a further €50m to bring the total budget for scheme to €300m.::Designated Area Payments - that additional funding of €10m must be allocated to the NPWS to pay farmers where restrictions to farming result from the designation of land.::Organic Farm Scheme (OFS) - that funding of the Organic Farm Scheme must be maintained at €12m and transitional arrangements put in place, given the current proposals under the Farm to Fork Strategy.::- An additional payment on the first 3ha of organic horticulture.  There is a clear growing market and demand for organic fruit and vegetables that will return a margin.::Knowledge Transfer (KT) - To support increased participation by farmers in KT programmes accorss all sectors, funding of €19m is required.  This would allow an extension of the KT programme for 2021 and allow additional participants into the scheme.::Producer Organisations (POs) - that €5m must be provided to assist farmers with the establishment and ongoing running costs of POs.::Walks Scheme - that the number of trails must be extended to 120, with additional funds of €2m to bring it to a total of €6m.::LEADER - that the LEADER Programme be fully funded for 2021, with no gap in this funding before the start-up of LEADER in the next RDP.::Targeted Agricultural Modernisation Scheme (TAMS)::- An allocation for TAMS for 2021 must be set at €120m.  It is necessary to meet all outstanding commitments and new application for 2021 under EU CAP transitional arrangements.::- Additional items must be added to include grant aid for road underpasses, weighbridges and rubber mats.::- There needs to be a separate investment limit for solar panels, similar to LESS and the ceiling for LESS needs to increase.::- In the context of fencing in inaccessible hill areas, the standard costings must reflect the increased cost in sheep fencing and of transporting materials to the site.::- The investment limit for the Pig and Poultry Investment Scheme (PPIS) increased to €200,000 per farmer announced in 2019 must be implemented as soon as possible.::- The minimum investment limit of €2,000 must be lowered to accommodate small investments.::- The standard costings must be adjusted in line with increased costs of building materials, machinery and labour.::Tillage - There must be greater flexibility in farm schemes so that tillage farmers qualify for higher grant rate payments, particulary in relatin to any new schemes, similar to the existing TAMS and GLAS schemes which were introduced under the CAP Pillar II.::Supporting Farmers through rexit and COVID-19::- Full compensation for any losses during Transition Period arising from Brexit uncertainty, sterling volatility and COVID-19 impact, across all sectors.::- Full compensation for beef price losses since the end of the period covered by the BEAM scheme on the 12th May 2019 involving the following   €160m from 12th May to 31st Dec 2019;  €113m from 1st Jan to 5th July 2020 (€163m losses less €50m pandemic payment); On-goijng losses estimated at €6m per week.::- The allocation of a€5bn Brexit Adjustment Rserve Fund as part of the EU Recovery Fund is welcome.  However, this may not be sufficient and must be scaled up as necessary to deal with all scenarios including the possibility of no deal, ie to provide for direct payments to farmers to fully compensate for the reduced value of the UK market, in addition to market support measures and longer term structural and adjustment funding.::- Further strengthening of the Government's Brexit contingency fund announced in Budget 2020, which allocated €110m to Agriculture, so that these funds are supplemented in Budget 2021.::Climate Action::- Funding is required to introduce a Sustainable Development Programme (SDP) to co-ordinate the delivery of price supports for farm-scale and community-based renewables and to ensure the maximum delivery of the Teagasc MACC climate roadmap.::- The 'new REPS-2 Programme' in the Programme for Government Our Shared Future must be piloted in 2021.::- There must be increased support to farmers with designated land.::- There must be an increased allocation for the Organic Farming Scheme.::- The BDGP has been effective in improving the efficiency of the national suckler cow herd.  This scheme must be simplified and built upon with an increse in the allocation for the scheme.::- There has been a bigger level of application than anticipated int he recently introduced BEEP-S scheme.  €35m was allocated under the scheme, an additional €17m is required to ensure all applicants are fully funded.::- The overall grant-aid available for the Low Emission Slurry Spreading (LESS) scheme must be increased to 60% and LESS equipment must be exempt from VAT.::- As per the commitment in the Programme for Government Our Shared Future, a liming programme to support farmers must be introduced, needing an allocation of €23m.::Renewable Energy & the Bioeconomy::- Tiered supports are required for the development of anaerobic digesters, ranging from farm scale up (up to 0.5MW), to community/small co-op scale )0.5MW - 2MW) and large co-op (5MW).::- The provision of a Capital Grant in the order of 50-60% which is ring fenced from existing farm supports and essentially brings new capital to a farm solar proposition. There needs to be flexible criteria around this grant to ensure participation of all farmers regardless of the sector, size or geographic location. Supports need to be tailored to take account of the west/east and north/south divide for farmers,ensuring a level playing field regardless of farm size, farm location or farm sector::- Development of a Feed in Tariff paid on the metered output of a solar installation and based on detailed financial modelling through the collection of funds from the carbon tax and the PSO Levy.::- Favourable Tax treatment to promote uptake on renewable technology for farm communities.  Revenue generated from renewable energy should be exempt from income tax for an extended period, as is the case with forestry.::- Inter Community Network Charges - Recognise the farming community as a virtual community in terms of auctions etc.  Create a framework for energy communities that would allow small auto-producers to share their excess without incurring system charges, therefore increasing export value.  This allows for energy trading between farmers.::- Finance - Government need to provide access to low/no interest finance to farmers and farm communities to encourage investment by the sector.::- RESS - Amend and simplify the terms of RESS to allow a farmer grouping (community) to bid in and receive support as a combined community project.::- Engage with the farming community to ensure there are no prohibitive network charges to deter investment in small scale renewable energy projects.::- Planning exemption for farmers for small scale developments.  One-stop advice clinics should be provided to assist project developers to submit successful applications.::Banking::- The Government through the SBCI must introduce a state backed guarantee (80%) low-cost interest (max 2.5%) loan scheme, which is accessible to all primary producers across all the farming sectors including aquaculture, forestry and amenity horticulture.::- The Scheme must   1/ Provide financial support to primary producers who are experiencing cashflow disruption and/or losing revenue due to the impact of COVID-19 virus.  2/ Operate through the main banks as heretofore with previous SBCI schemes, but also to include other financial institutions such as Credit Unions, An Post and other accredited asset lenders. 3/ Cater for loans up to €1,000,000 in the form of overdrafts, working capital and term loans in addition to asset finance.::- The Scheme must  4/ Offer a loan duration of up to 6 years in the case of term loans and asset finance.  5/  Provide for a 12-month moratorium on capital repayments.  6/ Ensure that the Government covers the interest payment for year 1.  7/ Not deny access to potential borrowers with insufficient security arising from reduced commodity prices and/or current asset valuations. 8/ Not use the family home as security. 9/ Not seek personal guarantees for loan amounts under €150,000.::- The Scheme must   10/ Not apply facility fees.  11/ Provide for a minimum loan value of €5,000.::Farm Forestry::- To restore the farmer premium differential as committed to in the Programme for Government Our Shared Future funding of €4m is required in 2021 based on the 8,000 ha planting programme.::- The introduction of a Harvesting Plan Grant to assist forest owners with the increased costs and requirements associated with applying for a felling licence.::- The introduction of an Ash Dieback Reconstitution scheme that appropriately compensats forest owners affected by the disease.  This would include the reinstatement of 15-year premiums on re-established woodlands and an option not to replant under certain circumstances.::- The introduction of a Payment for Ecosystem Services (PES) in recognition of the range of environmental services provided by forests, including carbon.  This payment would incentivise farmers to plant at the scale required and would provide income beyond the fifteen-year forest premium payments, as well as in subsequent crop rotations.::The removal of restrictions on planting productive marginal land.  In 2016 the COFORD Land Availability for Afforestation report identified 180,000 hectares of unenclosed land outside of environmental constraints that satisfies the eligibility criteria of the Afforestation and Woodland Creation scheme, which is currently excluded.::- The introduction of a Forest Owner Producer Organisation Scheme to provide supports for the preparation and implementation of Production and Marketing Plans for forest owner organisations.::- The development of a national Forest Certification scheme to overcome the obstable to private forest owner certification that mirrors similar successful schemes operating in other European countries.::National Food Ombudsman  -  The NFO must be adequately resourced and funded in order to effedtively tackle the imbalance of power in the food supply chain so that it is fair, transparent, well functioning and equitable.::Horticulture::- Funding for the scheme is increased to €10m in Budget 2021 to meet the demand for investment, evidenced by the oversubscription of the scheme in previous years.::- Compensation must be provided for the disposal of ash plants in the amenity hortiulture sector, arising from the Ash- Dieback disease.::Animal Health::- The Wildlife Control Programme must be resourced to proactively deal with all species of wildlife that are susceptible to TB and achieve eradication of TB within the shoretest feasible timeframe.::- The Government apply 0% VAT rate on non-oral animal medicines and vaccines.::- Direct funding support to farmers to off-set the costs associated with implementing additional biosecurity measures on their farms.::- Investment in developing and providing pen-side testing and analytical tools to farmers and veterinary practitioners to facilitate implementation of best practice advice for veterinary medicine usage.::- Commence the 10-year renewal programme in the Regional Laboratory Network as per the commitment in the Programme for Government Our Shared Future.::- Appropriate veterinary staff numbers must be provided in all Regional Veterinary Offices.::- Direct financial support for farmers for the testing costs associated with completion of the BVD eradication programme.::- Continuation of funding levels in the Johnes control programme.::- Funding for a Department of Agriculture administered National IBR programme.::- Dedicated budget for the Early Warning System (EWS).::Aquaculture::COVID-19 Market Disruption::- Subsidised scheme for loss of sales/reduction in production - 40% subsidy/single farm payment for reduced 2020 production and sales based on a 3-year average of verifiable annual production figures, compared with reduced prodution figure for 2020.::- Compensation for stock lost due to mortality losses/unsaleable stock as a result of over-stocked sites unable to sell due to lack of demand and no available markets.  Unsaleable stock losses to be assessed similar to 40% subsidy/single farm payment.::Implementation of Aquaculture Licensing Review Recommendations::-Adequate and appropriate resources must be allocatd to fully implement all the recommendations of the Independent Aquaculture Licensing Review.::- Sufficient funding must be provided to ensure the earliest possible implementation of Recommendation 8.2; pre-application process and Recommendation 8.5; the establishment of a web-based Aquaculture Application and Monitoring Sytem.::Blue Carbon Potential::Sufficient funding and resources must be allocated to the Marine Institute to facilitate this scientific research.  Consideration must be given to the role of the aquaculture industry as a carbon efficient source of sustainable protein and its contribution to marine ecosystem services.::Social Protection::Farm Assist::- The income disregard is incresed from the current level of 30% to 50%.::- In the means test for Farm Assist, the depreciation rate for farm equipment and machinery should be increased to a standard rate of 10% to more accurately reflect the useful life of these assets.::- The income disregards for agri-environmental schemes, included in the means test for Farm Assist, must be extended to also disregard forestry premium payments.::- The option of a three-year income test assessment be considered.::Fair Deal and Support for Older People::- Nursing Home Support Scheme (Amendment) Bill 2019 must be reintroduced immediately and provide for the inclusion of farm land leased to third parties, in line with other Government policy on inheritance under Agricultural Relief.::- Older people must be supported to live at home through incresed funding for the Home Care Package Scheme so that the number of hours provided is increased.::- The Total Contribution Approach (TCA) for calculating Contributory State Pension payments must be implemented in line with National Pension Framework (2008) agreement, which provides for total contributions of 30 years to qualify for a maximum payment.::- Credits must be provided to farmers on Farm Assist prior to 2007, when they were ineligible to make PRSI contributions under the scheme.::Farm Safety::- The introduction of a Farm Safety Scheme, with increased funding for health and safety equipment under TAMS.::- A handbrake and PTO improvement scheme, to include a PTO scrappage scheme and a handbrake replacement scheme, to assist farmers in replacing malfunctioning equipment.::- An annual farm safety budget be allocated to the Farm Safety Partnership Advisory Committee to implement future farm safety action plans.::Road Development::- Farmers impacted by national road developments under the new National Development Plan must receive a fleibility payment, reinstated to the value of €5,000/ac.",|Meeting|21-30::|Virtual Meeting|21-30::|Phone call|21-30::|Email|31-50::|Social Media|11-20,"Tim Cullinan IFA President, Damian McDonald IFA Director General, Chris Hill Wicklow IFA Chair, Jim O'Connor Roscommon IFA Chair, Des McHugh, Leitrim IFA Chair, Kathleen Henry Sligo IFA Chair, Gavin White Longford IFA Chair, Jarlath Walsh Mayo IFA Chair, Anne Mitchell Galway IFA Chair, Bernie McCarthy IFA Westmeath Chair.",No,,True,To lobby Oireachtas members regarding IFA 2021 Budget Submission - Expenditure Measures to Support Farm Enterprises,False,
66559,lobbying.ie/return/66559/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:22,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Health,S.I. No. 448/2020 - Health Act 1947 (Section 31A - Temporary Restrictions) (Covid-19) (No. 8) Regulations 2020,"Stephen Donnelly|Minister|Department of Health::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Helen McEntee|Minister|Department of Justice",Seeking clarification on the categorisation of countryside sporting activities under Level 5 COVID-19 restrictions.,|Phone call|2-5::|Letter|2-5::|Informal communication|2-5,"IFA Deputy President Brian Rushe, William Shortall IFA Countryside Executive",No,,False,,False,
66560,lobbying.ie/return/66560/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:35,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Matters involving public funds,Finance,IFA 2021 Budget Submission - Taxation Measures to Support Growth & Restructuring,"Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Michael Creed|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Holly Cairns|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Christopher O'Sullivan|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::David Stanton|Minister of State|Department of Justice and Equality::James O'Connor|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Pádraig O'Sullivan|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Colm Burke|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::John Brady|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Pat Casey|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Bernard Durkan|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Fiona O'Loughlin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::James Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Malcolm Byrne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Mark Wall|Senator|Seanad::Martin Heydon|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Patricia Ryan|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|Minister of State|Department of Defence::Verona Murphy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::James Lawless|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Marc Ó Cathasaigh|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::David Cullinane|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Jennifer Murnane O'Connor|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Shanahan|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Éamon Ó Cuív|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Denis Naughten|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Hildegarde Naughton|Super Junior Minister|Department of Climate Action, Communication Networks and Transport::Paschal Donohoe|Minister|Department of Finance::Michael McGrath|Minister|Department of Public Expenditure and Reform::Pearse Doherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Ciaran Cannon|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Aisling Dolan|Senator|Seanad::Claire Kerrane|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Patrick O'Donovan|Minister of State|The Office of Public Works::Fergus O'Dowd|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Erin McGreehan|Senator|Seanad::Colm Markey|Councillor|Louth County council::John McGahon|Senator|Seanad::Peter Fitzpatrick|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Ruairí Ó Murchú|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Kieran O'Donnell|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Mary Butler|Minister of State|Department of Health::Marc MacSharry|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brendan Griffin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Pa Daly|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Danny Healy-Rae|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Richard O'Donoghue|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Sean Fleming|Minister of State|Department of Finance::Robert Troy|Minister of State|Department of Enterprise, Trade and Employment::Michael Moynihan|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament::Cathal Berry|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Helen McEntee|Minister|Department of Justice and Equality::Damien English|Minister of State|Department of Housing, Planning and Local Government::Pauline Tully|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Carol Nolan|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Patrick O'Donovan|Minister of State|Department of Public Expenditure and Reform::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Sorca Clarke|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas","Farm Transfer, Succession and Partnerships - that Agriculture must be removed from the commercial definition and revised in line with the residential stamp duty charge of 1%, up to €1m, and 2% thereafter.::Reliefs for Stamp Duty::- The rollover of consanguinity relief post 2020 remains vital for farm transfer and planning.::- The extension of consolidation relief post 2020 is critical to incentivise farmers to reduce the number of parcels of land in their farm or to decrease the distance between them, with the net result of making their farm businesses more efficient and profitable.::- Young Trained Farmers Relief must be retained.  However, the age requirement of 35 years should be moved in line with the Department of Agriculture's Young Trained Farmer age maximum of 40 years and Revenue's age eligibility condition of the tax credit for succession farm partnerships, which is also up to 40 years.::- Reviews to Stamp Duty reliefs should be announced before Budget day in October.  Adeequate timing should be provided for in the year it is due for renewal, to support smooth transfer.::Ceiling for Young Trained Farmer Stamp Duty Relief::- Young Trained Farmer Stamp Duty Relief should be fully removed from State Aid or the ceiling be increased, to allow for greater land mobility, encourage land transfer and develop economically viable farm units.::Agricultural/Business Relief & Capital Acquisitions Tax (CAT) Values::- The retention of 90% Agricultural is critical to support the transfer of economically viable family farms.  The Association also supports the commitment in the Programme for Government to increase the Category A threshold (parent and child) from the current rate of €335,000 to €500,000 in future budgets.::- Due to changing demographics and family structures, the Favourite Nephew or Niece Relief should be extended to a Favourite Successor Relief, allowing the farm to be gifted to someone who would be in a better position to continue farming the land.  The movement from category B/C threshold to Category A would allow for less of a tax liability, protecting the sustainability of the farm and promote land mobility.::Collaborative Farming Partnership Fund::- The extension post 2021 of this essential grant, which is diminishing.::CGT Entrepreneur Relief::- If a landowner wishes to sell land to a long-term tenant, then the CGT Entrepreneur relief of 10% will apply to incentivise supporting the genuine farmer and giving the long-term tenant preferred status.::-The lifetime limit of €1m on the CGT Entrepreneur Relief should be increased in Budget 2021. The enhancement of CGT Entrepreneur Relief is an important measure to encourage risk-taking and investment, and the subsequent disposal of business assets during an individual's lifetime.::- Agricultural land that is subject to CPG should not be categorised as 'development' land and will still qualify for CGT Entrepreneur Relief.::Interaction of CGT Entrepreneur Relief & CGT Retirement Relief::- The interaction between the two CGT reliefs should be removed, and that the two reliefs should be standalone.  An individual should be able to avail, in full, of the CGT Entrepreneur Relief and The CGT Retirement Relief over the course of their lifetime, subject to satisfying the qualifying conditions of each relief.::Agricultural Relief - Removal of Individual Qualifying Criteria::- To encourage the transfer of a family farm into joing ownership at the time of inter-generational transfer, IFA believes that 90% Agricultural Relief should apply where the farm is transferred into joint names, and where the 80% asset test and the active farming requirement is satisfied by either of the spouses.::Forestry & CAT / Stamp Duty Reliefs::- If any percentage of the farm is dedicatd to farm forestry, it should be defined as agriculture land and the CAT Agricultural Relief applied to the whole farm.::- Farm forestry is treated in a similar manner in relation to the consanguinity and Young Trained Farmers Stam Duty Reliefs as it is with CAT Agricultural Relief, where it is defined as agriultural land.::- Where a non-farmer buys forestry, that the rate of stamp duty at normal commercial rates apply to the full value of land and timber.  This is to ensure forestry remains primarily with persons who are genuine farmers.::Extending 10-year Ownership and usage Period for CGT Retirement Relief to Spouse for Lifetime Transfers.::- Where a farmer has owned and used an asset for 10 years and the asset is transferred into joint names, the transferee spouse should inherit the same time ownership and usage status.::Income Volatility::Income Averaging 'Step-Out' flexibility::- A farmer should be allowed to 'step-out' of income averaging more than once in a five-year period, where they are not carrying an unpaid deferred tax amount from a previous 'step-out', providing a strong incentive to repay the deferred tax also.  For example, if the farmer 'steps out' from income averaging in Year 1 and repays the deferred amount in Years 2 and 3, they should be eligible to 'step-out' again in Years 4 or 5 of a cycle.::Agricultural Rainy-Day Fund::- The introduction of an agricultural Rainy-Day Fund, which allows all farmers to put aside a small percentage of their gross receipts, whether in their co-op, specially assigned bank account or State Farm Volatility Fund, which could be used by the NTMA.  This will create a buffer and ensure the long-term sustainability of the sector, which is very volatile.::cont'd   This money is then available for draw down within the next 5 years, and the tax due would be paid on the year of withdrawal, similar to how companies are allowed to offset their losses to protet the viability of the business by carrying it back from a loss making year to a profit making year.::Removing Discrimination in the Tax System::- The commitment in the Programme for Government Our Shared Future to increase the Earned Income Tax Credit to €1,650 for the self-employed, to match the PAYE credit must be implemented in full in Budget 2021.  The gap of €150 from the current level of €1,500, must increase to €1,650.::Universal Social Charge (USC) for the Self-Employed::- The discriminatino of the application of the USC between PAYE and self-employed earners must be removed, aligning the self-employed with PAYE workers.::Vaccines and Herd Health Products::- The Government apply 0% VAT rate on non-oral animal medicines and vaccines.::Tax Treatment of Payments Received for Use of Forestry Land by a Third Party::- Payment for the loss of this income i.e. forestry premium, should not be subject to Income Tax or Capital Gains Tax.::Carbon Tax Exemption on Agricultural Diesel & Other Agri-Fuels::- As there is no viable alaternative to using agri-diesel and other agri-fuels, the application of the carbon tax cannot incentivise behavioural change, therefore they should be exempted from the Carbon Tax.::CGT / CAT Reliefs - Solar Leases::- That the legislation is amended to give greater clarity and avoid the uncertainty that is impeding solar panel projets on farms.  The calculations used to determine the area of land on which solar panels are installed, should only include the footprint of the structures mounting solar panels, ancillary equipment and service roadways (i.e. areas not capable of being grazed).::cont'd   The calculations should exclude any area capable of being grazed by agricultural livestock either under, around or in between panels,::Green Tax Credit::- To ensure the advancement of farm scale renewable infrastructure  1/ a generation feed-in tariff must be introduced for farm-scale renewable energy prodution, in particular solar, wind and anaerobic digestion and 2/ Income received for the alternative use of farmland for renewable energy projects should receive an income tax exemption, if such income is used for the purposes of re-investment in the farm business.::Accelerated Capital Allowances for Emission Efficient Equipment::- Farm equipment, which contributes to increased emission efficiency, such as LESS or capital investment in developing bioeconomy supply chains, must qualify for accelerated capital allowances.  This would be provided through an enhanced SEAI Accelerated Capital Allowance scheme, or through a parallel scheme, which would operate under the same structures i.e. 100% capital allowances for investment in equipment that is independently certified and listed by a qualifying authority.::Farm Safety Incentive and Employee Flat-Rate Expenses::- Non-registered farmers may reclaim VAT on costs for purchasing and maintaining farm safety equipment to help maintain best safety standards, via the VAT 58 form.::- Agricultural workers be included as par of the current review of the flat-rate expenses, in line with similar employees in the sector, a rate of €651.70 is estimated.::Carbon Tax Relief::- Glasshouse growers of food crops using CO2 enrichment, should be granted a Carbon Tax relief/rebate.::Exise Duty on Fuel::- that the current rates on fuel and diesel remain unchanged.::Sugar Sweetened Drinks Tax (SSDT) and Healthy Eating::- The €35m revenue generated from the sugar tax on sweetened drinks, should be directed towards the promotion of the consumption of fresh and healthy Irish produce.",|Meeting|21-30::|Virtual Meeting|21-30::|Phone call|31-50::|Email|21-30::|Social Media|11-20,"Tim Cullinan, IFA President. Rose Mary McDonagh, IFA Farm Business Chair. Damian McDonald IFA Director General.",No,,True,To lobby all Oireachtas members regarding IFA 2021 Budget Submission - Taxation Measures to Support Growth & Restructuring,False,
66561,lobbying.ie/return/66561/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:37,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Trade,IFA 3-Step Brexit Emergency Plan,"Micheál Martin|An Taoiseach|Department of the Taoiseach::Thomas Byrne|Minister of State|Department of the Taoiseach::Damien English|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Peter Burke|Minister of State|Department of Housing, Local Government and Heritage::Martin Heydon|Minister of State|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Josepha Madigan|Minister of State|Department of Education and Skills::Norma Foley|Minister|Department of Education::Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Heather Humphreys|Minister|Department of Social Protection::Ossian Smyth|Minister of State|Department of Public Expenditure and Reform::Stephen Donnelly|Minister|Department of Health::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament::Brendan Gleeson|Secretary General|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::John Callinan|Second Secretary General|Department of the Taoiseach::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Paul Savage|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Seán Sherlock|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Deirdre Gillane|Chief of Staff|Department of the Taoiseach::Mary Butler|Minister of State|Department of Health::Vincent P Martin|Senator|Seanad::Pippa Hackett|Super Junior Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Robert Troy|Minister of State|Department of Enterprise, Trade and Employment::Michael McGrath|Minister|Department of Public Expenditure and Reform::Helen McEntee|Minister|Department of Justice and Equality::Mairead McGuinness|MEP|European Parliament::Malcolm Noonan|Minister of State|Department of Housing, Local Government and Heritage::Philip O'Callaghan|Special Adviser|Department of the Taoiseach::Diarmuid Lynch|Special Adviser|Department of the Taoiseach","Step 1 - Securing a deal    Trading conditions with the UK • Trade must be on the basis of tariff-free and quota-free access to the UK market. • The UK must respect the level playing field by maintaining corresponding standards on food safety, animal health and welfare, and the environment.::• No return by the UK to a cheap food policy. Future UK trade policy must not be allowed to undercut the EU for sensitive products such as beef, butter, cheddar cheese and lamb through lower tariffs or higher Tariff Rate Quotas (TRQs) for third country imports.::Full respect for the Irish Protocol – Deal or No-Deal  • To ensure unimpeded cross-border trade in goods between Northern Ireland and Republic of Ireland as currently applies.::Regulations at borders • Minimise time consuming administration and transit delays for shipping to or through Great Britain in the context of the Landbridge. • Fullest co-operation from the UK authorities to ensure the effective implementation of Green Lanes for the unimpeded transit of Irish trucks using the Landbridge to access the EU market.::Step 2 - Preparing the EU market for a limited-deal or no-deal  Suspension of EU imports • Imports of sensitive products from third countries, meat and dairy in particular, must be suspended. • Current beef imports from Mercosur countries of circa 250,000t should be stopped immediately. This is consistent with the recent vote in the EU Parliament against ratification of the EU-Mercosur trade agreement.::Suspension of EU trade negotiations on sensitive products • In any on-going negotiations with third countries, EU market access for sensitive products is off the table, until such time as there is full clarity as to the impact on the EU and global markets of the UK's exit from the EU.::Suspension of State Aid rules • The current suspension of State aid rules due to COVID-19 must be extended to allow member states to fully play their part in supporting the agriculture sector against the damage of Brexit from 1st January 2021.::Support for direct shipping to the EU - Deal or No-Deal • Immediate support for necessary infrastructure, including port facilities and shipping capacity in order to provide substantially increased regular, frequent, direct sea shipping links between Ireland and continental EU ports.::Step 3 - Supporting farmers in a limited-deal or no-deal €5bn EU Brexit Adjustment Reserve Fund • This must be scaled up as necessary to fully compensate farmers in all scenarios::• Supports to farmers - A majority portion of the €5bn EU Fund must be targeted to support Irish farmers whose incomes will be by far worst affected by Brexit. • Support for any necessary long-term structural adjustment, funded on a multi-annual basis.::Full compensation for any losses arising from Brexit including Sterling volatility  • Across all sectors – including beef, dairy, sheep, mushrooms, horticulture, cereals, pigs and poultry meat and seafood, which all stand to lose out substantially::Market disturbance and erosion of the incumbent importer position • Implementation of EU emergency measures funded from non-CAP resources, as in response to the 2014 Russian Embargo, to mitigate the impact on markets, produce and farmer prices and incomes of disturbances arising from the exit of the UK from the EU.::• The EU must be prepared to deploy the full range of market supports, including intervention, APS, export refunds and export credit insurance and legislate for these as necessary to protect producers against losses and stabilise markets.::Further strengthening of the Government's Brexit contingency fund for 2021 • The contingency allocation of €110m to Agriculture for 2020 must be rolled over and increased for 2021.::Loyalty to Irish product • Irish food processors with UK-based processing facilities must show loyalty to Irish product, in particular Irish beef, over third country imports.",|Meeting|6-10::|Email|11-20::|Informal communication|6-10::|Virtual Meeting|2-5::|Social Media|2-5::|Submission|1::|Letter|1,"Tim Cullinan IFA President, Bryan Barry IFA Deputy Director General, Liam MacHale IFA Director Brussels,  John Curran IFA Meath Chairman, Nigel Reneghan IFA Regional Chairman",No,,True,To lobby Oireachtas Members on IFA's Brexit Emergency Plan,False,
66562,lobbying.ie/return/66562/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:19,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Health,COVID-19 - Operation of Marts Under Restrictions,"Dara Calleary|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Brendan Gleeson|Secretary General|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Christopher O'Sullivan|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Creed|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Garrett Ahern|Senator|Seanad::Mattie McGrath|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Lowry|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament","To get COVID-19 restrictions lifted on Marts so that a limited number of purchasers of livestock complying with regulations be allowed into the sales ring.::To highlight that this is a critical time of year for our suckler farmers in the market place and it is vital the Mart sales function in as open, transparent and competitive a manner as is possible over the next number of weeks.::This is a crucial time of the year where Marts are operating at maximum capacity as cattle come off grass and suckler farmers sell their weanlings, the option to hold these cattle does not exist for the majority of farmers selling at this time of year.::Any disruption to the marketing of these animals can have very serious consequences in terms of animal health, welfare and crucially income for the farmers involved in what is a low-income sector at best.::Online System - The online bidding system has bedded down very well in some Marts as a supplementary system to a presence of buyers in the ring. However, there are huge concerns about Marts operating exclusively under this system and in particular at this time of year when throughput is at peak numbers.::Not all buyers are comfortable using this system and there is a concern that they will not be active bidders. This could reduce the number of bidders and affect the integrity of the market.::Given the essential nature of providing an effective market outlet for cattle and sheep at this time of year and the consequences of this not being available, we are requesting a review of the current measures and the facilitation of limited numbers of buyers at ringsides.::That a strictly limited number of buyers would be allowed around the ring with full Government guidelines for social distancing and the wearing of masks applied.Mart rings are generally very spacious, with high roofs and many openings with good airflow.",|Phone call|2-5::|Letter|1::|Meeting|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|1::|Email|2-5::|Social Media|1,"Tim Cullinan IFA President. Jarlath Walsh Chairman Mayo IFA, Roy O'Brien IFA Regional Executive, Damian McDonald IFA Director General.",No,,False,,False,
66563,lobbying.ie/return/66563/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:18,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Bovine TB Herd History Risk Statement and Report Letters,"Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Martin Blake|Chief Veterinary Officer|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Brendan Smith|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Niamh Smyth|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Pauline Tully|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe O'Reilly|Senator|Seanad::Joe McHugh|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Padráig Mac Lochlainn|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Pearse Doherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Robbie Gallagher|Senator|Seanad::Heather Humphreys|Minister|Department of Social Protection::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Patrick Donohoe|Special Adviser|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Timmy Dooley|Senator|Seanad::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Eugene Murphy|Senator|Seanad::Martin Heydon|Minister of State|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine","Meeting to discuss issues surrounding Bovine TB Herd History Risk Statement and Report Letters::Requirements in the TB Programme   -::1)	Re-establishment of an effective Wildlife Control Programme based on density reduction of susceptible species.::2)	A full in-depth investigation of the sources of all TB outbreaks to identify and remove the source must be implemented.::3)	Financial support for farms impacted by TB restrictions.::Advancing IFA position on the TB programme::To make the case that the black listing of farmers through the TB Herd Rish letters has devalued animals on 20,000 farms",|Letter|2-5::|Phone call|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|6-10::|Email|2-5::|Social Media|6-10,"Tim Cullinan IFA President, Pat Farrell IFA Animal Health Chair",No,,False,,False,
66565,lobbying.ie/return/66565/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:17,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Legislation,Agriculture,Protected Geographical Indication (PGI) Status for 'Irish grass-fed beef',"Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Sinead McPhillips|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Brendan Gleeson|Secretary General|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Brendan Smith|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Heather Humphreys|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Niamh Smyth|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Pauline Tully|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe O'Reilly|Senator|Seanad::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament",Concerns around Department of Agriculture's 'objection' process around Bord Bia's application for PGI status for 'Irish grass-fed beef'::Proper engagement with farmers who are key stakeholders in this process.::Crucial that the application has broad support amongst farmers.::It is vital that the obtaining of PGI status can deliver added value and a real additional return for farmers.::Pause the objection process to allow for engagement with IFA and farmers.,|Letter|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|2-5::|Phone call|6-10::|Meeting|2-5::|Informal communication|2-5::|Email|2-5,"Tim Cullinan IFA President. Damian McDonald IFA Director General, Brendan Golden IFA Livestock Chair Tomas Bourke, IFA Senior Policy Executive.",No,,False,,False,
66566,lobbying.ie/return/66566/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:14,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Legislation,Environment,Restrictions on Lead Ammunition,"Malcolm Noonan|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament","To highlight the concerns with regards to the proposed restrictions on lead ammunition over wetlands::Proposal is disproportionate and discriminatory toward farmers.::IFA is opposed to the new regulation as it will place excessive restrictions on farmers carrying out their duties in wetlands, and undue expense to upgrade their shotguns to a safe standard to fire steel gunshot.::Request meeting to discuss this issue.",|Letter|2-5::|Email|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|1::|Phone call|2-5::|Informal communication|2-5::|Social Media|1,Tim Cullinan IFA President.,No,,False,,False,
66567,lobbying.ie/return/66567/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:13,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Economic Development and Industry,National Economic Social Council (NESC),Martin Fraser|Secretary General|Department of the Taoiseach,End of term - Letter of thanks for contribution,|Letter|1,Damian McDonald IFA Director General,No,,False,,False,
66568,lobbying.ie/return/66568/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:12,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Health,COVID-19 - IFA's Resilience Workshops for Farmers,Mary Butler|Minister of State|Department of Health,"Launch IFA initiative invitation to Minister::To highlight that, Connecting for Life, Ireland's National Strategy to Reduce Suicide 2015-2020 identified farmers as a vulnerable group at increased risk of suicidal behaviour. IFA is very concerned as the winter approaches and the uncertainty of the pandemic continues for the well-being of farmers and their families.::That research has showed that resilience training can help farmers identify realistic, practical wellness activities to better cope with the multitude of work stresses which they face on a daily basis.::To highlight taht IFA is developing a new initiative of resilience workshops for farmers in response to these concerns. These on-line workshops aim to help farmers to build and strengthen their resilience in advance of the winter months, to protect against stresses and mental illness as we all adjust to the new normal.",|Letter|1::|Email|1,"Tim Cullinan IFA President, Caroline Farrell IFA Farm Family Chair",No,,False,,False,
66569,lobbying.ie/return/66569/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:11,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Environment,Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) Advisory Committee,"Eamon Ryan|Minister|Department of Climate Action, Communication Networks and Transport",Provide IFA Nominee to the EPA Advisory Committee,|Letter|1::|Email|2-5,Tim Cullinan IFA President,No,,False,,False,
66570,lobbying.ie/return/66570/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:11,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Matters involving public funds,Agriculture,Tillage Sector Crisis,"Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine","To highlight that the Irish tillage sector is facing serious issues and challenges, however, there are also opportunities which need to be supported and encouraged by government.::To show that the Irish tillage sector  contributes over €650m of farm gate value to the rural economy. It is of critical strategic importance to Ireland's €13bn livestock, dairy, food, drinks and mushroom export sectors.::- The area of Irish grain production is down 17% since 2012. Increase grain production through supports.::- Tillage farm incomes fell by 15% in 2019 compared to 2018. Preliminary estimates by IFA indicate that at current spot grain and straw prices, the overall farm gate value of the Irish tillage sector could fall by a further 15% this year. Need to improve income on tillage farms.::- Irish tillage farmers were disproportionately affected by the last CAP. The next CAP could have serious economic consequences for the sector, not least in relation to proposals regarding the overall budget, convergence, capping and eco schemes. Ensure a fair CAP for tillage farmers.::Ireland imported 1 million tonnes of maize from third countries such as Brazil in the 2019/2020 marketing season. This is double the figure we imported 5 years ago. These imports, which are produced to lower regulatory and environmental standards, are undermining the value of quality assured Irish grain. Reduce importation of grain.::Access to low cost finance.  support for renewables and limited R&D.::To highligh the loss of Plant Protection Products (PPP's)::To sdeek access to new crop breeding technologies::To seek support for renewables.::Request meeting to discuss tillage sector issues.",|Letter|1::|Informal communication|2-5,"Tim Cullinan IFA President, Mark Browne IFA Grain Chair",No,,False,,False,
66571,lobbying.ie/return/66571/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:09,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Marine,Aquaculture - Sustainable Development,Pippa Hackett|Senator|Seanad,"The implementation of the ‘Aquaculture licensing review recommendations' continues to be a key policy for IFA Aquaculture, seeking a clear commitment from Government with regard to an implementation plan that prioritises and gives clear timelines for each of the recommendations outlined in the review. Reform of the licensing and regulatory system for Irish Aquaculture is vital for the sectors sustainable development.::Growing demands for more sustainably sourced seafood along with the goals of the EU Green Deal Farm to Fork and Biodiversity strategies, provide a real opportunity for the aquaculture sector to position itself as part of the solution to these growing demands and acknowledging the role Aquaculture has to play in sustainable food production and the Covid-19 recovery plan.::Discuss commitments outlined in the Programme for Government ‘Our Shared Future', to develop the aquaculture sector in a sustainable way.::Implementation of the recommendations in the report of the Independent Aquaculture Licencing Review Group.::Identification, designation and management of Marine Protected Areas (MPAs) in Irish territorial waters in line with EU Biodiversity strategy .::Recognition for ‘blue carbon' potential and the role sustainable Irish aquaculture can play to achieve this.::Request meeting to discuss various issues outlined above.",|Letter|2-5::DMcD/BG - 01/10/20|Phone call|1,Tim Cullinan IFA President. Michael Mulloy IFA Aquaculture Chair. Damian McDonald IFA Director General,No,,False,,False,
66572,lobbying.ie/return/66572/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:08,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Taxation,Carbon Tax on Agri-Diesel,Paschal Donohoe|Minister|Department of Finance::Michael McGrath|Minister|Department of Public Expenditure and Reform,"To demonstarte that there is no viable alternative to agri-diesel. Therefore, the carbon tax does not incentivise behavioural change and is penal on farmers.::The current rebate system for carbon tax on agri-diesel is cumbersome and is not open to all farmers or agri-contractors. As a result, many farmers are unable to claim back the carbon tax paid or pay for it indirectly because it is passed on by agri-contractors. Nevertheless, it is imperative that the current rebate system is maintained in the absence of an exemption.::That agri-diesel should be exempt from carbon tax.",|Letter|1::|Email|1::|Virtual Meeting|1::|Informal communication|2-5,"Tim Cullinan, IFA President.",No,,False,,False,
66573,lobbying.ie/return/66573/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:07,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Legislation,EU Affairs,Proposal for a Regulation amending Regulation (EU) No 1308/2013 establishing a common organisation of the markets in agricultural products,Mairead McGuinness|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament,"Regarding the vote in the European Parliament plenary of 19-22 October, on the Proposal for a Regulation amending Regulation (EU) No 1308/2013 establishing a common organisation of the markets in agricultural products ('Regulation 1308/2013'), we want to bring to your attention the issue of the use of the meat and dairy sales denominations to market vegetarian and vegan foodstuffs.::Amendment 165 must be adopted to ensure that the use of terms such as 'steak', 'sausage', 'escalope', 'burger' or 'hamburger' are for products that exclusively contain meat. The use of such terms to describe plant-based products is misleading to the consumer and must be avoided.::Similarly, we support the adoption of Amendment 171 to maintain and enhance the current provisions set out in Article 78 of the Regulation, read in conjunction with Part III of Annex VII of Regulation 1308/2013 (Milk and Milk Products). These provisions reserve the use of terms such as 'milk', 'cheese', 'yoghurt', 'butter' or 'whey' exclusively to products that contain dairy milk.::Rejection of these amendments would undermine the reputation and nutritional quality of our beef and dairy produce.",|Letter|1::|Email|2-5,Tim Cullinan IFA President,No,,False,,False,
66574,lobbying.ie/return/66574/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:07,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Legislation,"Food ",COVID-19 - Food Chain,"Micheál Martin|An Taoiseach|Department of the Taoiseach::Deirdre Gillane|Chief of Staff|Department of the Taoiseach::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|MEP|European Parliament::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament","To highlight the importance of all parts of the Food Chain remaining operational and marts are able to function as we prepare for the busy Autumn trade in event of further government restrictions due to COVID-19.::To demonstrate that the food supply chain of farming, processing and retailing is essential. Every effort must be made to safeguard the health of everybody while keeping the supply chain moving.::The flexibilities that were introduced last Spring around farm visits for inspections, etc, should be reviewed and updated as appropriate.::Keep our ports operating so that food and livestock can continue to move within the single market and to third countries.::It is important that farmers and workers in the food sector are regarded as essential workers in the event of another lockdown. That this is recognised in any further support measures or restrictions being implemented by the Government.::To highlight the impact of border closures on the movement of agri-food exports to the continent, and on the efficiency of the food supply chain",|Letter|1::|Email|2-5,Tim Cullinan IFA President.,No,,False,,False,
66575,lobbying.ie/return/66575/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:06,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Legislation,Environment,Nitrates Regulation,"Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Darragh O'Brien|Minister|Department of Housing, Local Government and Heritage::Peter Burke|Minister of State|Department of Housing, Local Government and Heritage::Martin Heydon|Minister of State|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Pippa Hackett|Senator|Seanad::Brendan Gleeson|Secretary General|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Bill Callanan|Chief Inspector|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament","Raise concerns regarding the timelines proposed to increase the nitrogen excretion rate from the dairy cow from 85kg N/ha to 89kg N/ha, prior to the formal review of the regulations next year.::This amendment, and especially the timing of its implementation, must be the subject of formal consultation, giving farmers an adequate lead-in-time to adjust their management practices.::A review of Ireland's Nitrates Action Programme is due in 2021. The review is typically an opportunity to engage with IFA and other stakeholders in a formal consultation process, through which key issues can be discussed and addressed.::Request meeting to discuss this very important issue prior to any implementation decision. We would ask that the necessary consultation takes place with IFA to address this issue as part of the overall Nitrates Regulations review next year.",|Letter|6-10::|Phone call|1::|Meeting|1::|Virtual Meeting|1,"Tim Cullinan, IFA President. Paul O'Brien, IFA Environment Chair. Damian McDonald IFA Director General. Brian Rushe IFA Deputy President. Jim O'Connor IFA Roscommon Chair, Des McHugh IFA Leitrim Chair, Kathleen Henry IFA Sligo Chair",No,,False,,False,
66576,lobbying.ie/return/66576/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,20/01/2021 22:02,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Legislation,Employment,Employment Permits,"Leo Varadkar|An Tánaiste|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Damien English|Minister of State|Department of Housing, Planning and Local Government","Some agriculture sectors particularly dairy, horticulture, pig and poultry continue to experience labour shortages on their farms. There is currently a shortage of skilled, semi-skilled and manual labour for farming enterprises. The mushroom sector in particular, is presently struggling to recruit suitable workers, and this is having a serious effect on the efficiencies of businesses in the sector.::Work permits for applicants from non-EEA countries.::Changes to the occupational lists, to re-categorise farm assistants/operatives which are currently part of the ineligible list for labour permits. This would allow prospective farmer employers to routinely apply under the general labour permit system to obtain permits for non-EU/EEA workers.::IFA welcomed the Employment Permits (Consolidation and Amendment) Bill 2019 and its proposal to take certain operational elements out of primary legislation, ensuring that the rules governing employment permits for non-EEA nationals can be nimbler and better adapted to the evolution of the Irish labour market. This Bill, among other amendments, would allow for the introduction of a seasonal worker scheme.::In order to cater for the demand within the farming sector, IFA is requesting an immediate reopening of the existing pilot scheme - General Employment Permit Scheme.::IFA seeks meeting to discuss these issues.",|Letter|1::|Email|2-5,"Tim Cullinan, IFA President",No,,False,,False,
66577,lobbying.ie/return/66577/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:04,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Matters involving public funds,Agriculture,Poultry Disease Compensation Fund,"Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Paula Barry Walsh|Deputy Chief Veterinary Officer|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine","The Poultry Working Group, of which IFA is a member, are seeking co-finance from the Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine (DAFM).::DAFM to administer the disease fund and levy collection on an ongoing basis.::€5 million initial input from DAFM and €2.5million annually thereafter to the fund.",|Virtual Meeting|1::|Submission|1,"Andy Boylan IFA Poultry Chair, Robert Malone IFA Poultry Executive",No,,False,To inform elected representatives of the Economic report the Poultry sector in Ireland. ask to assist in lobbying DAFM for financial support for a poultry disease fund.,False,
66578,lobbying.ie/return/66578/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:02,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Heritage,Land Designations,"Malcolm Noonan|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas","Engagement with the Government on the designation of land and the implications arising for farmers and landowners.::Concluding an agreement in relation to the designation, funding and management of Special Areas of Conservation, Special Protection Areas and Natural Heritage Area.::IFA's Budget 2021 proposals for allocation of €10m funding the NPWS Farm Plan Scheme.::Rewetting of bogland - implications for farmers::Forestry in Hen Harrier areas",|Virtual Meeting|1::|Email|2-5::|Letter|1::|Social Media|1,"Tim Cullinan, IFA President, Flor McCarthy IFA Hill Chair, Gerry Gunning IFA Rural Development Executive",No,,False,,False,
66579,lobbying.ie/return/66579/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:01,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Ireland's National African Swine Fever (ASF) control measures,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad",Increase the awareness of the threat of ASF to Ireland's pig industry and to look for political support to increase funding for the National Disease Control Centre and it role in implementing Ireland's National African Swine Fever (ASF) control measures.::Support for an All-Ireland policy to prevent ASF enter the island of Ireland.,|Meeting|1::|Informal communication|2-5::|Submission|1,"Roy Gallie IFA Pigs Chairman, Robert Malone IFA Pigs Policy Executive",No,,False,,False,
66580,lobbying.ie/return/66580/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:59,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Organic Farm Scheme,"Pippa Hackett|Senator|Seanad::Colm Hayes|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Bill Callanan|Chief Inspector|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Donal Coleman|Director|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine","To secure continued funding of the organic farm scheme::To ensure any future re-opening of the scheme is correctly managed. The last reopening of the scheme was based on a flawed pointed system, in which smaller farm holdings were discriminated against::To emphasise the need for increased marketing for the sector::To address the lack of competition in the organic beef and lamb sectors::To ensure that the current scheme is rolled over for farmers under the CAP transition period::The new scheme must be open for longer than the four-week period of the last scheme so that farmers will have time to get the necessary paperwork in place. Rejected applicants from the last reopening of the scheme must be prioritised and allowed access into the scheme with immediate effect. In addition, farmers who continued to farm organically but who were denied access to the scheme, must be paid retrospectively.::Knowledge transfer (KT) and advisory services are crucial for any new entrants into organic farming. The continued support of your Department with extra resources for new entrants is vital.::We need basic research into grassland and cereal production, such as the use of inter-cropping which is being used by conventional and organic farmers in Ireland. This would meet the goals set out in the Farm to Fork strategy  to reduce fertilizer and pesticides.::Organic farmers must not be excluded from any new REPS scheme under the new CAP. In the past, several measures under the GLAS scheme were contradictory to organic farming practises.::Organic farmers outside of the Bord Bia Quality Assurance Scheme should quality for the new Beef Finisher Payment. Organic farmers are inspected annually for their certification status, this should suffice as Bord Bia assured certification. Beef finishers received this funding for market losses incurred as a result of the COVID-19 pandemic. Organic farmers were equally if not more impacted by this pandemic.",|Email|6-10::|Letter|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|1::|Informal communication|2-5,IFA President Tim Cullinan. Nigel Reneghan IFA Organic Project Team Chair.,No,,False,,False,
66581,lobbying.ie/return/66581/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:58,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Matters involving public funds,Agriculture,Investment Aid Scheme for the Development of the Commercial Horticulture Sector,"Pippa Hackett|Senator|Seanad::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament","Funding for the Horticulture Sector::The provision of €1m in funding for the National Food Ombudsman is a step in the right direction to tackling Unfair Trading Practices (UTPs) in the food supply chain. The Government now needs to go beyond the EU Directive on UTPs and tackle unsustainable discounting and tendering of fresh produce.::Opportunity to develop the Irish seed potato and fresh chip sectors.::Introduce a targeted investment aid scheme, which will cater for equipment specific to the seed sector and construction of ambient potato storage facilities.::Stakeholder groups are endeavouring to develop opportunities in relation to import substitution. The continued support of your Department for these projects will be vital if they are to prove successful.::The harvesting of peat for use in the horticulture sector - action and assistance required.::Reopening of the pilot work permit scheme - action and assistance required.",|Letter|1::|Virtual Meeting|1::|Email|2-5,Tim Cullinan IFA President. Paul Brophy IFA Horticulture Chair.,No,,False,,False,
66582,lobbying.ie/return/66582/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:57,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Legislation,Sports and Recreation,COVID-19 - Restrictions on Recreational Game Shooting,"Helen McEntee|Minister|Department of Justice::Malcolm Noonan|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas",Seeking clarification relating to recreational game shooting involving people from not more than two households in the current COVID-19 Level 5 restrictions.::IFA Countryside is of the view that it is not accurate to describe all game shooting as a sport. A large amount of recreational hunting takes place by individuals. This is not a business or organised sport such as tennis or golf.::That this form of recreational exercise complies with the current restrictions. Game shooting is a recreational outdoors exercise which involves one or two people from within their locality.::Game shooting should be permitted once it is in compliance with the guidelines.::Pheasant shooting season runs from November 1st to 31st January. Clarification is required,|Letter|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|1::|Email|2-5,"Tim Cullinan IFA President, Brian Rushe IFA Deputy President",No,,False,,False,
66583,lobbying.ie/return/66583/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:56,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Trade,Live Exports,"Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Brendan Gleeson|Secretary General|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Pippa Hackett|Super Junior Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Patrick Donohoe|Special Adviser|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine","To express serious concerns re draft proposals recently circulated to some live exporters regarding increased conditions on live exports.::To highlight that some of the proposals in this document, which has now come into the possession of IFA, could cause significant disruption to the live export trade.::To highlight that reports from the Netherlands in relation to proposals to stop imports from Ireland are concerning for the dairy sector in particular.::To highlight that closure of food service outlets in Europe due to the COVID-19 pandemic and the potential implications this could have on European veal markets.::Request meeting to discuss these concerns.",|Letter|1::|Phone call|1::|Virtual Meeting|2-5,Tim Cullinan IFA President. Damian McDonald IFA Director General.,No,,False,,False,
66584,lobbying.ie/return/66584/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:54,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Legislation,Agriculture,Forestry Felling Licenses,"Pippa Hackett|Senator|Seanad::Brendan Gleeson|Secretary General|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Colm Hayes|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Robert Troy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Peter Burke|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament::Patrick Donohoe|Special Adviser|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine","IFA is seeking a reform of the forest licence system so forest owners  does not have to wait longer than 4 months for a forestry licence as set out in the Forestry Act 2014.::Forest road and felling/thinning licence applications that are in the system for more than four months must be automatically approved under an amnesty provision.::Amend the Forestry Act 2014 to introduce new exemptions for activities, such as forest road construction and thinning operations and replace with a single consent system at afforestation stage so farmers can manage their forests according to best forest practice. .::Review the current appropriate assessment (AA) screening process, associated rules and thresholds.::A cost-based planning support grant should be introduced, as referenced in the Mackinnon report, to assist with increased costs and requirements associated with applying for a felling and afforestation licence::The appointment of an external Project Manager within the Department to implement the operational changes recommended in the Mackinnon report to develop an appropriate and effective licensing system.::The newly introduced Reconstitution and Underplanting Scheme (Ash Dieback) does not adequately support forest owners for the financial losses incurred and must be redesigned to support owners to reconstitute all infected plantations and remove the replanting obligation under certain circumstances.",|Meeting|1::|Email|2-5::|Phone call|6-10::|Virtual Meeting|1::|Social Media|6-10,"Tim Cullinan IFA President,  Damian McDonald IFA Director General, Vincent Nally, IFA Farm Forestry Chair & Geraldine O'Sullivan, Senior Policy Executive",No,,False,,False,
66585,lobbying.ie/return/66585/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:53,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Legislation,Energy and Natural Resources,Use of Peat in the Horticultural Industry / Stakeholder Group,"Malcolm Noonan|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Eamon Ryan|Minister|Department of Climate Action, Communication Networks and Transport","On the Stakeholder Group::That IFA's submission to the consultation process launched into the use of peat in the horticultural industry would be taken on board.::As part of the consultation process, the inter-departmental working group on the use of peat in horticulture has recommended the establishment of a wider working group to examine the broader issues.::In order to have balanced debate on the issue, it is important that all the key industry stakeholders are part of this working group. In this regard, the growing media companies who produce the peat, and the primary horticulture producers who are the end users, must be at the table.::Usage of Peat in the Horticultural Industry::Due to a Supreme Court decision earlier this year, there has been no harvesting of peat on bogs over 30ha resulting in big reduction of stocks required by the horticulture sector.::There is no commercial alternative currently available to the use of peat, a point which is expanded on in IFA's submission  to the consultation process into the use of peat in the horticultural industry and also in Teagasc's submission on same.::As a result of this Supreme Court case, procedures around applying for leave to apply for substitute consent are required. We understand the Department of Housing, Planning and Local Government are currently drafting legislation to rectify this particular matter. However, even if this is resolved, companies still have to apply for substitute consent from An Bord Pleanála, then planning from Local Authorities and finally a licence from the EPA.::Even in a best-case scenario one is looking at a timeframe of 2 to 5 years.::In the event of Irish peat not being available, it will be imported adding extra costs to production, while also adding to the carbon footprint of the plants and crops produced.::Importance for our horticulture producers to have access to Irish peat for the viability of the industry.",|Letter|2-5::|Email|1,Tim Cullinan IFA President. Paul Brophy IFA Horticulture Chair. Val Farrell IHNSA Chair.,No,,False,,False,
66586,lobbying.ie/return/66586/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,20/01/2021 22:02,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Marine,Aquaculture - National Marine Planning Framework,"Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Darragh O'Brien|Minister|Department of Housing, Local Government and Heritage::Peter Burke|Minister of State|Department of Housing, Local Government and Heritage::Diarmuid Lynch|Special Adviser|Department of the Taoiseach::Kevin Dillon|Special Adviser|Department of the Taoiseach","Ongoing development of the National Marine Planning Framework (NMPF).::The NMPF, address a number of recommendations outlined in the recent ‘Review of the Aquaculture Licensing Process', where the report concluded that the aquaculture licensing system was in ‘urgent need of reform'.::IFA notes that the Department of Agriculture, Food & Marine (DAFM) is not referenced in the Marine Planning and Development Management Bill (MPDM) and it would appear that proposed legislative framework currently does not apply to the aquaculture sector - making it the only sector in marine space currently exempted from the proposed legislative framework underpinning the marine planning system.::This will mean that the policies, principles and objectives of the NMPF mean little in regard to the aquaculture sector if they are not underpinned by appropriate legislation.::Any legislative framework related to the marine planning system must include the Aquaculture sector to enable better integrated marine management.::The Irish Aquaculture sector needs the support of policy to allow for sustainable development of the industry.::Request a meeting to discuss the decision to exclude Aquaculture in the MPDM Bill and that DAFM opts in with the NMPF process, in line with commitments outlined in the current 'Programme for Government'.",|Letter|1::|Phone call|1::|Email|1,Tim Cullinan IFA President. Michael Mulloy IFA Aquaculture Chair,No,,False,,False,
66587,lobbying.ie/return/66587/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:52,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Legislation,Environment,General Scheme of Water Environment (Abstractions) Bill - Pre-Legislative Scrutiny,"Darragh O'Brien|Minister|Department of Housing, Local Government and Heritage::Peter Burke|Minister of State|Department of Housing, Local Government and Heritage","Under the current Nitrates Action Programme, a wide range of farm-level measures have been implemented with additional measures to be implemented at the start of 2021. In addition, the Teagasc Agricultural Catchment Programme and Agricultural Sustainability Support and Advisory Programme (ASSAP), which integrate scientific research with farm advice, have been working with farmers to implement the right measure in the right place at farm level.::How will the inevitable lag time between implementation of improved management practices and water quality be accounted for by Department of Agriculture in the upcoming presentation to the European Commission, Nitrates Committee as part of the Nitrates Derogation review process?::Discuss concerns on the General Scheme of Water Environment (Abstraction) Bill, particularly the lack of a provision under Head 17 – Compensation to require Irish Water to publish a national package that sets out arrangements to support Irish Water and landowners to efficiently and fairly proceed through the process. This is a well-established and much-replicated model that has been proven to be a fair model to compensate impacted landowners.::Request meeting to discuss these concerns.",|Letter|1,Tim Cullinan IFA President.,No,,False,,False,
66588,lobbying.ie/return/66588/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:51,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Social Protection,Personal Public Service Numbers (PPSN),Heather Humphreys|Minister|Department of Social Protection,"Address the considerable backlog in processing PPSN applications.::To point out that while we understand these are unprecedented times, the current backlog (over 10 weeks in some cases) is simply not acceptable.::To highlight that in some cases, horticultural workers have arrived into the country without having their applications processed which results in them not being able to work.::Shortage of labour for horticultural operations, growers reliant on internatinal workers for harvest work. Need to stop Ireland's reputation being damaged as workers will not return because of this issue.::Employers should not be forced to foot the bill in cases wherre the employees have had to return home.::This problem needs to be addressed as a matter of urgency.",|Letter|1::|Email|1,Tim Cullinan IFA President,No,,False,,False,
66589,lobbying.ie/return/66589/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:51,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Legislation,Community,Control of Dogs,"Malcolm Noonan|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas","Advance the issue of better dog control within Government Departments and Agencies who have responsibility in this area.::We need a similar traceable system in place for dog owners similar to farmers who provide full traceability for the 7m cattle and 3m breeding sheep under their care from birth, where every animal is individually tagged and traceable to the person responsible for them.::It is estimated that there are 800,000 dogs in the country with only 217,261 identified, leaving almost 600,000 without identification or association to a responsible keeper.  Uncontrolled dogs are causing serious animal health and welfare issues for our animals and significant financial losses as a result of attacks and killings that occur.::Dog owners are required to have a dog licence and to have their dogs microchipped.  Oligations of dog owners must be enforced.::The lack of compliance with these obligations is unacceptable and cannot be allowed to continue. Local Authorities must enforce the current obligations on dog owners in a more effective way.::There is an urgent need to strengthen the legislation, include appropriate sanctions and develop a single national database identifying dogs and their owners.::More needs to be done by local authorities through enforcement and information and awareness campaigns for dog owners, pointing out their obligations and the damage their uncontrolled dogs are doing to farm animals.",|Letter|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|1::|Social Media|1,Tim Cullinan IFA President. Sean Dennehy IFA Sheep Chair.,No,,False,,False,
66590,lobbying.ie/return/66590/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:50,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Local Government,M20 Motorway Limerick to Cork - New Route,"Kieran O'Donnell|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas",To make public representatives aware of the treatment of land owners along the route and the lack of information available to them,|Virtual Meeting|1::|Informal communication|2-5,"Shay Galvin, Limerick IFA Co Chairman",No,,False,,False,
66591,lobbying.ie/return/66591/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:45,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,GLAS (Green Low-Carbon Agri-Environment Scheme),"Paul Dillon|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine","To Influence Policy, gather information and ensure rollover of the Scheme into 2021.",|Phone call|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|1,"Michael Biggins IFA Rural Development Chairman, Flor McCarthy IFA Hill Farming Chairman, Brendan Golden IFA Livestock Chairman, Mark Browne IFA Grain Chairman, Denis Griffin IFA Policy Executive",No,,False,,False,
66592,lobbying.ie/return/66592/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:42,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Legislation,Justice and Equality,Personal Insolvency (Amendment) (No. 1) Bill 2020,Helen McEntee|Minister|Department of Justice,Remove Section 115A (18) (b) of the Personal Insolvency Act so that a relevant debt no longer needs to have originated prior to January 2015.::Amend Section 115A (18) (a) of the Personal Insolvency Act to include debt secured in or over the debtor's income reliant/core asset as relevant debt in addition to debt secured in or over the debtor's private principal residence.,|Letter|1::|Email|1,"Tim Cullinan, IFA President",No,,False,,False,
66593,lobbying.ie/return/66593/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:41,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Flooding in South Galway / Shannon Areas,"Patrick O'Donovan|Minister of State|Department of Public Expenditure and Reform::Michael O'Connor|Special Adviser|The Office of Public Works::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament","To influence policy and reduce consequences of flooding in the South Galway / Shannon areas::That the OPW would manage water levels on the Shannon river by dropping the level from the end of the summer season, while ensuring that it doesnt cause problems further downstream.::That a number of key pinch points identified along the river are addressed::That the silt that had been building up on the bed of the Shannon over the years is removed by dredging",|Phone call|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|1::|Email|1::|Social Media|2-5,"Tim Cullinan IFA President, Elaine Farrell IFA Oireachtas, Pat Murphy IFA Connaught Chair, Willie Dolan IFA Regional Executive, Roy O'Brien IFA Regional Executive, Denis Griffin IFA Policy Executive, Anne Mitchell IFA Galway Chair, Imelda Walsh Tipperary N. County Chair, Richard Scally IFA Offaly Chair, Bernie McCarthy IFA Westmeath County Chair, Shay Galvin IFA Limerick Chair.",No,,False,,False,
66594,lobbying.ie/return/66594/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:36,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Proposed New REPS (Rural Environment Protection Scheme),"Colm Hayes|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Paul Dillon|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine","To influence policy, gather information and ensure Scheme is open in 2021 and payment issued in 2021.",|Phone call|1,Denis Griffin IFA Policy Executive,No,,False,,False,
66595,lobbying.ie/return/66595/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:34,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Matters involving public funds,Agriculture,Compulsorary Purchase Order (CPO),"Alan Farrell|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe O'Brien|Councillor|Fingal County Council",That famers' views would be listened to and be taken on board in advance of any CPO process,|Email|1::|Phone call|1,James McGrane IFA Dublin Chair,No,,False,,False,
66596,lobbying.ie/return/66596/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:31,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Marine,COVID-19 Aquaculture Support Scheme,"Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Cecil Beamish|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Brendan Gleeson|Secretary General|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament",Announcement and roll-out of the Covid-19 Aquaculture Support Scheme worth €1.5m has ended on a somewhat positive note for the Irish shellfish industry::Adoption of EU Commission amended regulations to allow Member States to redirect available EMFF funds in response to the Covid-19 crisis::Commitment to implementation of the recommendations of the Aquaculture Licensing review and reform of Aquaculture licensing system in line with Prog for Govt,|Virtual Meeting|1::|Phone call|1::|Informal communication|2-5::|Email|2-5::|Social Media|2-5,"Tim Cullinan IFA President, Micheal Mulloy IFA Aquaculture Chairman, Teresa Morrissey IFA Aquaculture Executive. Damian McDonald IFA Director General.",No,,False,,False,
66597,lobbying.ie/return/66597/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:47,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Organic Farm Scheme - funding and rejected applicants,"Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Pippa Hackett|Super Junior Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Colm Hayes|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine",To identify the number of farmers who applied to the scheme in 2018 who did not get into the scheme but continued to farm organically and therefore remained registered as organic farmers in 2019.,|Email|2-5::|Informal communication|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|1,Nigel Renaghan Organic Project Team Chairman,No,,False,,False,
66598,lobbying.ie/return/66598/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:35,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Matters involving public funds,Agriculture,Ash Dieback Disease,"Marian Harkin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas",Seeking support for farmers who have Ash Dieback Disease. Trees are rotting very quickly and falling down before they are fully dead. Farmers should not have to pay for the disposal of these trees.,|Email|1,"Declan Smyth, Ballinamore, Co Leitrim IFA Branch Secretary",No,,False,,False,
66599,lobbying.ie/return/66599/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:26,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Common Agriculture Policy (CAP) 2021 - 2027,"Paul Dillon|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Brendan Gleeson|Secretary General|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Thomas Byrne|Minister of State|Department of the Taoiseach::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Paul Savage|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine","Advancing IFA policy on the farm schemes and CAP::Full funding for existing farm schemes in CAP transition phase.::Continuation of GLAS, ANC, TAMs, BDGP, BEEP-S, Sheep Welfare and Organic Shemes with payments being maintained.::€10m increased funding for the NPWS Farm Plan Scheme in designated areas.::Increased allocation of €2m for the Walks Scheme, with an increase in the number of walks supported to 120.::Maximum permissible level of national co-financing of 57% in the CAP Rural Development Programme post 2020.::The commitment in the Programme for Government for a “new REPS-2 Programme”, must be in addition to the national co-financing commitment from the Government.",|Phone call|2-5::|Meeting|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|2-5::|Informal communication|2-5::|Social Media|2-5,"Tim Cullinan IFA President, Damian McDonald IFA Director General.",No,,False,,False,
66600,lobbying.ie/return/66600/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:19,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Trade,Sheep Meat Exports to Mainland Europe - COVID-19 Border Closures,"Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Pippa Hackett|Senator|Seanad","The border closures that are in place for COVID-19 controls between the UK and Europe have the potential to severely impact on our sheep meat exports to mainland Europe, a market we rely heavily on.::Since the sudden closure of the Eurotunnell, the landbridge route to continental Europe is no longer an option.::Markets in France, Germany and Belgium are vital for our sheep meat sector and access to these is severely impacted as a result of the closure.::To secure free movement of our essential products through the land bridge route.::Viable alternatives to the landbridge route must be put in place, to ensure we continue to have unhindered access to our key market which is vital for sheep farmers.",|Email|2-5::|Phone call|1,"Sean Dennehy, IFA Sheep Committee Chair",No,,False,,False,
66601,lobbying.ie/return/66601/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:18,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Sheep Welfare Scheme Reference Years,"Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine","IFA are requesting that all farmers in the scheme are provided with the opportunity to have their reference numbers brought up to date to accurately reflect the level of activity on the farm.::To highlight the rigid adherence of the Terms and Conditions of the scheme to date, with the reference numbers established in 2014 and 2015 has effectively reduced the level of support available to sheep farmers. Where numbers have reduced on participant farms or where farmers exited the scheme this money has been lost to the sector.::To highlight the constraints of the historic reference period, which is based on 2014 and 2015 numbers has meant that progressive sheep farmers, who are the future of the sector, are penalised with low numbers of eligible sheep.::To highlight that the reference period is now 6 years out of date and with the scheme running for a further 2 years, will be 8 years out of date at the end of the transition period.::To secure this critical amendment to a scheme that sheep farmers depend on to ensure the scheme supports fairly the progressive sheep farmers who are vital in sustaining the future viability of the sector.::To highlight that this scheme was initially announced with a budget of €25m, which was never fully drawn down. €17m has been allocated for 2021 for the scheme.",|Letter|1::|Email|2-5::|Social Media|1,"Tim Cullinane, IFA President. Sean Dennehy, IFA Sheep Chair",No,,False,,False,
66602,lobbying.ie/return/66602/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:09,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Import of seed potato from the UK,"Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas","To determine if the government has any plans to expand the seed sector in Ireland. Ireland imports over 50% of its potato seed requirements, mainly from the UK . The implications of a hard Brexit, will mean that potato seed from the UK, will not be allowed into Ireland after Jan 2021. This represents an opportunity to expand local seed production.",|Email|2-5,"Thomas McKeown, IFA National Potato Chairman",No,,False,,False,
66603,lobbying.ie/return/66603/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:07,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Review of the Agriculture Appeals Act 2001,"Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Seán Canney|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament",Establishment of an Agricultural Appeals Review Panel to include a farmer nominee and an Independent Chair. This will enhance the appeals process and provide greater assurance to farmers.::Farmers do not perceive the current appeals office to be sufficiently independent.::IFA acknowledge the commitment in the recent Programme for Government  to establish this review panel and we would like to see its implementation as soon as possible.::Request meeting to discuss same.,|Letter|1::|Email|2-5,"Brian Rushe IFA Deputy President, Enda Monaghan Galway IFA",No,,False,,False,
66604,lobbying.ie/return/66604/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 16:06,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Legislation,Health,Nursing Home Support Scheme - A Fair Deal,"Mary Butler|Minister of State|Department of Health::Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Joe McHugh|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Heather Humphreys|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Denis Naughten|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Richard Boyd Barrett|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Jack Chambers|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brendan Griffin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Padráig Mac Lochlainn|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Mattie McGrath|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Cian O'Callaghan|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Thomas Pringle|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Duncan Smith|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Marc Ó Cathasaigh|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Seán Ó Fearghaíl|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Anne Rabbitte|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Malcolm Byrne|Senator|Seanad::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament",To progress the amendment to the Nursing Home Support Scheme legislation and introduce a three year cap on family farms subject to certain criteria being met.,|Virtual Meeting|1::|Email|11-20::|Phone call|1::|Social Media|1,"Tim Cullinan IFA President, Caroline Farrell IFA Farm Family & Social Affairs Chair, Geraldine O'Sullivan, IFA Senior Policy Executive",No,,False,,False,
66605,lobbying.ie/return/66605/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 15:05,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Areas of Natural Constraint (ANCs),"Paul Dillon|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Charlie McConalogue|Minister of State|Department of Justice","To Influence Policy, gather information::Ensure rollover of the Scheme into 2021.",|Phone call|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|1::|Social Media|1,"Michael Biggins IFA Rural Development Chair, Flor McCarthy IFA Hill Farming Chair, Brendan Golden IFA Livestock Chair, Denis Griffin IFA Policy Executive",No,,False,,False,
66606,lobbying.ie/return/66606/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 15:04,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Local Government,Louth County Council Development Plan 2021-2027,"Mairead McGuinness|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|Councillor|Louth County council::Peter Fitzpatrick|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Imelda Munster|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Gerald Nash|Senator|Seanad::Fergus O'Dowd|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::John McGahon|Senator|Seanad::Erin McGreehan|Senator|Seanad::Ruairí Ó Murchú|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::John Sheridan|Councillor|Louth County council::Pearse McGeough|Councillor|Louth County council::Dolores Minogue|Councillor|Louth County council::Hugh D Conlon|Councillor|Louth County council::Jim Tenanty|Councillor|Louth County council::Joanna Byrne|Councillor|Louth County council::Kevin Callan|Councillor|Louth County council::James Byrne|Councillor|Louth County council::Paddy McQuillan|Councillor|Louth County council::Michelle Hall|Councillor|Louth County council::Tom Cunningham|Councillor|Louth County council::Edel Corrigan|Councillor|Louth County council::Sean Kelly|Councillor|Louth County council::Conor Keelan|Councillor|Louth County council::Antoín Watters|Councillor|Louth County council::Emma Coffey|Councillor|Louth County council::Marianne Butler|Councillor|Louth County council::Maria Doyle|Councillor|Louth County council::Liam Reilly|Councillor|Louth County council::Kevin Meenan|Councillor|Louth County council::Tomás Sharkey|Councillor|Louth County council::Maeve Anna Yore|Councillor|Louth County council","Zoning - The County Development Plan should not set heritage and conservation against rural people, to the detriment of both. Emphasis should be on facilitating people to live in, and contribute to, the communities where they grew up, whether they wish to raise their families there or to retire back there.::Natural Heritage, Biodiversity and Green Infrastructure - Louth Co Co should act in line with the policy objective above and develop and implement a plan with local shareholders to control bracken on the Cooley mountains. Damage caused by increased recreational use in the Carlingford Mountain SAC needs to be acknowledged and a sustainable recreational plan needs to be developed with shareholders and interested parties.::Renewable Energy Projects - On-farm Renewable Energy projects connecting to the grid via the local Substations should be facilitated and encouraged in the new Plan. Farmers should be fairly supported and incentivised by local and national government.::County Development Plan - This and future County Development Plans should have IFA included so as to fully represent the views of farmers in the county of Louth.::N2 Ardee to Castleblaney Road Project - Louth Co Co must continue to keep in touch with affected land owners and treat them fairly in the process. Local councillors must also put pressure on political colleagues in the Dail to restore the CPO Goodwill Payment to €5,000 per acre",|Email|1,John Carroll IFA Louth County Chair,No,,False,,False,
66607,lobbying.ie/return/66607/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 15:03,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Code of Practice for Farmers' Data,"Brendan Gleeson|Secretary General|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine","To seek information from the Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine to assist IFA in preparing a draft Code of Practice in relation to farmers' data.::As part of this process, IFA is seeking the following information as it applies::•	Which entities and organisations do you share farmer data with?::•	What data processing agreements do you have in place with these entities, organisations and institutions?::•	Do you aggregate data for circulation or publication? If so, can you list the places where it's published or who it is circulated to?::•	Do you have any research partnerships or joint projects underway with any other organisations or institutions that require data sharing?::•	Do you receive any fees for any data you provide?::•	Do your data and privacy policies address the ownership, access to and control of farmers' data?",|Letter|1,Damian McDonald IFA Director General.,No,,False,,False,
66608,lobbying.ie/return/66608/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 15:02,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Transport,Statement of Strategy 2020-2023 - Department of Transport,"Ken Spratt|Assistant Secretary|Department of Transport, Tourism and Sport","In accordance with the Public Service Management Act, 1997 the Department of Transport is in the process of preparing a three-year Statement of Strategy following the recent appointment of our new Minister, Eamon Ryan, TD and Minister of State, Hildegarde Naughton, TD.::The Statement will cover the period 2021 to 2023. It will establish our guiding mission for those years, define our priorities and set out a path to achieving those priorities.::How Department should frame our medium and long term high level goals and objectives to best align with the outcomes you are aiming to achieve over the period 2021 to 2023 and beyond; and::Any matters of a cross-cutting nature which you feel we should prioritise to ensure that we bring a whole of sector perspective to the complex challenges facing both of our organisations.",|Email|1::|Letter|1,Tim Cullinan IFA President.,No,,False,,False,
66609,lobbying.ie/return/66609/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 15:02,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,"Statement of Strategy 2021 - 2024 - Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine","Bill Callanan|Chief Inspector|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine","The Public Service Management Act, 1997, requires that Secretaries General prepare and submit a Statement of Strategy to their Minister within 6 months of his or her appointment as a Minister.::Arising from the recent appointment of a new Minister for Agriculture, Food and the Marine, the Department is in the process of preparing a new Statement of Strategy to serve as a framework for action over the next 3 years.::i)	The external environment in which we operate and our ability to adapt to changing circumstances (e.g. Brexit, European Green Deal, Covid 19 adaptation, new CAP);::ii)	leadership role of Dept in the implementation of the new agri-food 2030 Strategy, which is in its development stage, Harnessing Our Ocean Wealth and Forestry 2030;::iii)	The requirements of the agri-food actions set out in the; Programme for Government (Our Shared Future); the Government's Climate Action Plan; Future Jobs Ireland 2019, Action Plan on Rural Development and its successor Action Plan on Regional and Rural Development;::iv)	Other overarching policy frameworks e.g. Our Public Service 2020, Civil Service Renewal, etc.::The Mission of the Department in the 2016 - 2019 Statement of Strategy  was ‘Serving the government and people of Ireland by leading, developing and regulating the agri-food sector, protecting public health and optimising social, economic and environmental benefits'.",|Letter|1::|Email|1,Tim Cullinan - IFA President,No,,False,,False,
66610,lobbying.ie/return/66610/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 15:00,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Legislation,Environment,Climate Action and Low Carbon Development (Amendment) Bill 2020,"Brendan Gleeson|Secretary General|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament","To highlight that while meeting the climate targets will be a challenge, farmers are ready to play their part::To highlight the frustration for farmers is that they are getting no credit for the carbon they are sequestrating on their farms. The net carbon position on farms must be looked at that takes into account carbon offset as well as carbon emitted.::To ensure a balanced make up of the Climate Action Council::To ensure a role for Bord Bia and Teagasc in Climate Action::Treatment of Biogenic Methane - to acknowledge in the Bill of the cyclical nature of methane in GHG emissions accounting methodology.::That the Bill facilitates farmers to be part of the climate solution::The need for a balanced treatment of Agriculture in the Climate debate.",|Phone call|1::.|Meeting|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|1::|Email|2-5,"Tim Cullinan IFA President, Damian McDonald IFA Director General",No,,False,,False,
66611,lobbying.ie/return/66611/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:58,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Energy and Natural Resources,Solar Energy,"Bill Callanan|Chief Inspector|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Paul Kenny|Special Adviser|Department of Climate Action, Communication Networks and Transport","To brief the Department of Agriculture on a new IFA Solar Project for farmers.::To put forward the business case, to secure a grant from Department to make the proposal work for all farmers.::To demonstrate the possiblity of using TAMS or SEAI for the grant.::Secure meetings to discuss the Project in further detail and take Department of Agriculture through a Presentation in more detail.",|Email|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|2-5::|Meeting|1,"Martin Stapleton IFA Treasurer, Damian McDonald IFA Director General. James Kelly IFA Director of Organisation, Peter Clarke Head of Strategic Projects.",No,,False,,False,
66612,lobbying.ie/return/66612/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:57,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Environment,"Ag Climatise - A Roadmap towards Climate Neutrality Report - published by Department of Agriculture, Food & the Marine","Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament",To highlight that farmers are committed to reducing emissions::That the focus would be on supporting farmers to adopt specific mitigation measures and technologies to imporve productivity and efficiency on farms. This will achieve emissions reduction.::That Government policy must support Tillage and Horticulture sectors.::That issues concerning labour availability and peat extraction must be addressed immediately.,|Email|2-5,Tim Cullinan IFA President,No,,False,,False,
66613,lobbying.ie/return/66613/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:56,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Development of New Suckler Brand,"Brendan Gleeson|Secretary General|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Sinead McPhillips|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine",The development and promotion of a farmer controlled brand for beef from the suckler herd.::That the suckler beef brand would reflect the additional societal and environmental value of suckler beef production through premium marketing of this product.,|Phone call|1::|Meeting|1::|Virtual Meeting|1::|Informal communication|2-5,Damian McDonald IFA Director General. Tim Cullinan IFA President. Tomas Bourke Senior Policy Executive,No,,False,,False,
66614,lobbying.ie/return/66614/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:53,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,EU Affairs,Brexit Stakeholders Forum,"Simon Coveney|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Thomas Byrne|Minister of State|Department of the Taoiseach::Helen Blake|Assistant Secretary|Department of the Taoiseach::Chris Donoghue|Special Adviser|Department of Foreign Affairs::Aingeal O'Donoghue|Assistant Secretary|Department of Foreign Affairs","To engage with the Minister for Foreign Affairs and Officials at the Department on :::the importance of securing a zero-tarriff, zero-quota trade deal and on;::the Future Relations; the implementation of the Northern Ireland / Ireland protocol and the prepardness for a deal or a no-deal scenario",|Virtual Meeting|2-5::|Informal communication|2-5,"Tim Cullinan IFA President, Bryan Barry IFA Deputy Director General",No,,False,,False,
66615,lobbying.ie/return/66615/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:47,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Beef Taskforce Stakeholder Group,"Sinead McPhillips|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament",That farmers would be in the majority on the monitoring group to oversee the grass-fed Protected Geographical Indicator (PGI)::Change of IFA Nominee on the Taskforce::To emphasise the importance of developing a suckler brand to complement the Grass-Fed PGI. That this would be developed and led by farmers who can direct Bord BIa rather than the other way around,|Virtual Meeting|2-5::|Letter|1::|Email|2-5,"Tim Cullinan IFA President, Tomas Bourke IFA Policy Executive",No,,False,,False,
66616,lobbying.ie/return/66616/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:46,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Agri-Food Strategy 2030,"Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Sinead McPhillips|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Bill Callanan|Chief Inspector|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Martin Blake|Chief Veterinary Officer|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine",Ensure Ireland's Agri-food Strategy 2030 includes measurable targets to improve farm incomes and viability.,|Virtual Meeting|2-5::|Informal communication|2-5,Tim Cullinan IFA President,No,,False,,False,
66617,lobbying.ie/return/66617/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,20/01/2021 22:10,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,EU Affairs,Common Agriculture Policy (CAP) Consultative Committee,"Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Brendan Gleeson|Secretary General|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Paul Savage|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine",Ensure that current Irish farming practicies satisfy eco-scheme requirements under the Green Architecture of the CAP,|Virtual Meeting|2-5,Damian McDonald IFA Director General. Denis Griffin IFA Rural Develpment Executive,No,,False,,False,
66618,lobbying.ie/return/66618/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:45,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Targettted Agricultural Modernisation Scheme (TAMS),"Paul Dillon|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine","To Influence Policy, gather information and ensure rollover of the Scheme into 2021.",|Phone call|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|1,"Michael Biggins IFA Rural Development Chair, Flor McCarthy IFA Hill Farming Chair, Brendan Golden IFA Livestock Chair, Mark Browne IFA Grain Chair, Thomas McKeown IFA Potato Chair, Denis Griffin IFA Policy Executive, Tomás Bourke IFA Executive, Niamh Brennan IFA Policy Executive.",No,,False,,False,
66620,lobbying.ie/return/66620/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:43,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Beef Data Genomics Programme - BDGP,"Paul Dillon|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|Senator|Seanad::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament::Charlie McConalogue|Minister of State|Department of Justice","To influence policy and ensure rollover of the scheme into 2021.::To welcome the issuing of the BDGP payments to farmers.::To highlight that the number of farmers who met the key 50% female replacement requirement of 4 or 5 star animals is important.::To make the case for farmers who are within one animal of meeting the 90% compliance level for the female replacement rate of 50%, to significantly reduce the penalties on these farmers.",|Phone call|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|1::|Email|2-5::|Social Media|1,"Michael Biggins IFA Rural Development Chair, Flor McCarthy IFA Hill Farming Chair, Brendan Golden IFA Livestock Chair, Denis Griffin IFA Policy Executive, Tomás Bourke IFA Livestock Executive",No,,False,,False,
66621,lobbying.ie/return/66621/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:41,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Sheep Welfare Scheme,"Paul Dillon|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament::Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine","To Influence policy and ensure rollover of the Scheme into 2021.::That the reference years of the Sheep Welfare Scheme for the CAP transition period would be changed::To highlight that the reference years do not accurately reflect the current flock of may sheep farmers withing the scheme and need to be changed::That new entrants would be allowed in the scheme::To point out that of the €25m originally allocated to this scheme, four year on on €17m has been drawn down, which leaves room for new entrants.",|Phone call|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|1::|Email|1::|Social Media|1,"Sean Dennehy IFA Sheep Chair, Michael Biggins IFA Rural Development Chair, Flor McCarthy IFA Hill Farming Chair",No,,False,,False,
66622,lobbying.ie/return/66622/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:39,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Beef Environmental Efficiency Programme - Sucklers (BEEP-S),"Paul Dillon|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament::Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine","To Influence policy, gather information and ensure rollover of the Scheme into 2021.::That there would be flexibility from the Department on the dates of application given the disruption caused by the COVID-19 controls and concerns of some farmers attending marts or having service providers on their farms::That farmers who have implemented all measures in the BEEP-S scheme must receive their full payment",|Phone call|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|1::|Email|2-5::|Social Media|2-5,"Michael Biggins IFA Rural Development Chair, Flor McCarthy IFA Hill Farming Chair, Brendan Golden IFA Livestock Chair",No,,False,,False,
66623,lobbying.ie/return/66623/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:38,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Beef Exceptional Aid Measure - BEAM,"Paul Dillon|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament","To ensure that the Department of Agriculture issues up-to-date statements for farmers that are easy to follow to measure compliance for the BEAM scheme 5% reduction.::To ensure that farmers are provided with regular and straightforward updates, setting out their position in relation to the 5% reduction and the facility to monitor in real time their reduction target",|Phone call|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|1::|Email|1,"Brendan Golden IFA Livestock Chairman, Tomas Bourke  IFA Policy Executive",No,,False,,False,
66624,lobbying.ie/return/66624/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:34,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Matters involving public funds,Agriculture,€2bn COVID-19 Credit Guarantee Scheme (CCGS),"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament","To welcome the opening of the new €2bn COVID-19 Credit Guarantee Scheme to provide farmers with access to low cost loans as they respond to the impacts of COVID-19::To highlight that the cash burn arising from COVID-19 is unstainable and is a threat to the viability of many SMEs, including farming.::To demonstarte that this low-cost COVID-19 CCGS will address working capital needs in order to protect upstream and downstream employment as well as the productive capacity of the agri-sector::That the Government seek an extension of the EU Temporary Aid Framework to enable the COVID-19 CCGS to be extended beyond year end.",|Email|2-5,"Tim Cullinan IFA President, Rose Mary McDonagh IFA Farm Business Chair",No,,False,,False,
66625,lobbying.ie/return/66625/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:32,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Matters involving public funds,Agriculture,COVID-19: €50m Beef Finishers Payment (BFP) Scheme.,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament::Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine","That the payment to farmers under this scheme would be made without delay::To highlight that the closing date for applicatons was in September, that it was now November and that farmers who had incurred losses earlier in the year have severe cashflow pressures::That any surplus monies in the scheme, when outstanding appeal cases are dealt with, must be directed towards cattle that were exported for direct slaughter. These animals incurred the same losses as those processed in the country and can easily be identified from their export certificates.",|Email|2-5::|Social Media|1,Brendan Golden IFA Livestock Chair,No,,False,,False,
66626,lobbying.ie/return/66626/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:31,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Legislation,Finance,Finance Bill 2020,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament","To welcome the renewal of consanguinity relief and consolidation relief under the stamp duty code in the Finance Bill 2020.::To highlight that these reliefs are vital to the sustainability and viability of the agricultural sector by reducing teh effective rate of stamp duty on transfers of agricultural land from 7.5% to 1% in certain circumstances.::That the Young Trained Farmer relief from stamp duty, due to expire on 31st December 2021, will be extended.",|Email|1,Rose Mary McDonagh IFA Farm Business Chair,No,,False,,False,
66627,lobbying.ie/return/66627/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:28,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,TB Programme Costs,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament","To highlight that the Department of Agriculture's presentation of costs of the TB programme do not properly account for farmers' input.::To highlight that there is a lack of appreciation and respect for the time and money farmers put into the TB Programme, compounded by the failure to recognise TB breakdowns on farms are events that are outside the farmer's control.::To highlight that farmers contribute €35m directly each year to the TB programme and a further €20m in labour, which the Department continually ignores, bringing the total contribution of farmers to €55m, representing almost 50% of the programme costs.",|Email|1,Pat Farrell IFA Animal Health Chair,No,,False,,False,
66628,lobbying.ie/return/66628/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:27,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Legislation,EU Affairs,Brexit Agreement -  24th December 2020,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament","To highight that while the deal reached between the EU and the UK is a relief, that it will pose significant difficulties for the Irish agri-food sector.::To acknowledge the work of both side to avoid a 'no-deal'::To higlight that farmers have real concerns about how non-tariff barriers will impact on our ability to keep trade flows moving. It's important that the Green Lanes are prioritised for food exports from 1st January 2021.::That the €400m support fund for Irish farmers is ready in the new year to address market distrurance.::That the €5bn Brexit adjustment fund must also be available",|Email|2-5,"Tim Cullinan IFA President, Jim O'Connor, IFA Roscommon Chair",No,,False,,False,
66629,lobbying.ie/return/66629/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 17:34,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Matters involving public funds,Agriculture,€10m Pilot Scheme - Tillage Sector,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad",To welcome the announcement of the Pilot Scheme in the agri-environment area::That tillage farmer participants in the existing GLAS scheme must be able to avail of the new pilot scheme,|Email|1,Mark Browne IFA Tillage Chair,No,,False,,False,
66630,lobbying.ie/return/66630/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:25,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Local Government,Greenway Projects,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament",That Local Authorities would adopt a National Greenways Strategy whereby they would consult and be proctive with potentially affected landowners::To make it know that IFA will reflect on the decision of An Bord Pleanala in relation to the South Kerry Greenway and analysise the implications for farmers / landowners in Kerry and across the country,|Email|1::|Informal communication|2-5,"Paul O'Brien IFA Environment Chairman, Pat O'Driscoll IFA Kerry Chair",No,,False,,False,
66631,lobbying.ie/return/66631/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:24,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Matters involving public funds,EU Affairs,EU Budget,"Brendan Gleeson|Secretary General|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine",EU Recovery Fund::That funding goes directly to farmers who will take the brunt of any fallout from currency fluctuations and trade and logistical issues that will arise once the deal reached before Christmas works its way through the system.::To outline the real concerns about how non-tariff barriers will impact on our ability to keep trade flows moving. Green Lanes have been implemented previously for food exports. These must be prioritised to allow us reach our markets.::To highlight that longer-term implications for our food exports could be the flooding of the UK market by cheap imports. Farmers here on the island of Ireland and in the UK are steadfast in their view of standards.::To stop any race to the bottom.,|Phone call|1,Damian McDonald IFA Director General,No,,False,,False,
66632,lobbying.ie/return/66632/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:20,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,EU Affairs,Plant Based Products,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament","That Irish MEPs would accept both amendments on the plenary vote on meat and dairy denominations in the EU Parliament, which would protect our industry and consumers::The the amendments would succeed in securing words suck as 'steak', 'sausage', 'escalope', 'burger' or 'hamburger' for products that exclusively contain 'meat', and 'milk', 'cheese', 'yoghurt' 'butter' or 'whey' for products that exclusively contain dairy.::That plant-based products must not be deliberately disguised as something thay are not.",|Email|1::|Letter|1::|Informal communication|2-5,Tim Cullinan IFA President,No,,False,,False,
66633,lobbying.ie/return/66633/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:19,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Matters involving public funds,EU Affairs,€5bn Brexit Contingency Fund,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament::Thomas Byrne|Minister of State|Department of the Taoiseach::John Callinan|Second Secretary General|Department of the Taoiseach::Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine","That Irish farmers and the Irish agri-food industry would be top of the queue for the €5bn Brexit Contingency Fund as we are the sector worst affected by Brexit.::That there is recognition when the fund is being allocated,  that even with a deal there will be regulatory barriers to trade and a real risk that teh value of the UK market will be undermined.",|Email|2-5::|Meeting|1::|Informal communication|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|2-5,Tim Cullinan IFA President,No,,False,,False,
66634,lobbying.ie/return/66634/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:17,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,EU Affairs,Anti-Dumping Measure on Ammonium Nitrate (AN),"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|MEP|European Parliament::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament","To highlight that the decision by the European Commission to prolong anti-dumping measures on Ammonium Nitrate from Russia for another five years is a further blow to European agriculture as Irish farmers continue to face high-priced nitrogen fertiliser prices in a market devoid of fair competition.::In the review of Antidumping measure on AN from Russia, to request an intervention in contacting Commissioner Dombrovskis (Trade) and Commissioner Wojciechowski (Agriculture) asking for their support not to renew Anti dumping measure on Ammonium Nitrate from Russia",|Email|2-5,"Tim Cullinan IFA President, Liam MacHale IFA Director Brussels",No,,False,,False,
66635,lobbying.ie/return/66635/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:16,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,EU Affairs,EU Green Deal,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament","To highlight the serious contradictions and lack of policy coordination under the Green Deal, CAP and Trade policy::To highlight that under the Green Deal, the EU is driving up costs and want organic production standards at conventional prices, while at the same time under the Mercosur trade deal, the EU Commission is importing beef that fails to meet EU standards and would be illegal to produce in the EU.::That the family farm model and economic sustainability is placed top of the Green Deal agenda by both politicians and policy makers::That the EU Commission learns the hard lessons from COVID-19 and recognises the importance of health, food security and food sovereignty for Europe",|Email|1,Brendan Golden IFA Livestock Chair,No,,False,,False,
66636,lobbying.ie/return/66636/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:15,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Trade,Mercosur Trade Deal,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine",That the EU Commission does not continue to ignore the mounting evidence of Brazil's degradation of the environment for beef exports::To point out that the Commission was explicit that Mercosur could not go ahead if Brazil failed to meet environmental standards. A new report from the University of Oxford and the nature Conservancy says the deal fails the sustainability test and should be abondoned.::To welcome the vote in the European Parliament that emphasises that the EU-Mercosur agreement cannot be ratified as it stands::That the Minister for Agriculture uses the EU Agriculture Council Meeting (November 2020) to re-state opposition to the Mercosur trade deal and support the Austrian position and four other member states who are opposed to it.,|Email|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|2-5::|Informal communication|2-5::|Social Media|1,Tim Cullinan IFA President,No,,False,,False,
66637,lobbying.ie/return/66637/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:14,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,EU Affairs,EU Farm to Fork and Biodiversity Strategies,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament",That the EU would complete a full impact assessment of the EU Farm to Gork and Biodiversity Strategies::To highlight that there has been no consideration given to their impact on output or on production costs of farmers.::To ensure that farmers are not let carrying the cost::That Teagasc would also carry out an assessment of the impact here in Ireland::To highlight that the US Department of Agriculture has examined the EU Farm to Fork and Biodiversity Strategies and predicts that farm incomes would be reduced by 16% as a result of the strategies but that neither the EU or Ireland has carried out the exercise.,|Email|1,Tim Cullinan IFA President,No,,False,,False,
66638,lobbying.ie/return/66638/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:13,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Common  Agriculture Policy (CAP) - National Strategic Plans,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament","To highlight that the recommendations issued by the EU Commission in relation to the the national strategic plans under the CAP are a shot in the dark as they not backed up by an impact assessment::To highlight that the recommendations will lead to reduced output, reduced productivity and increased costs.::That the Government instructs Teagasc to carry out a full analysis before any of the recommendations are progressed",|Email|1,Tim Cullinan IFA President,No,,False,,False,
66639,lobbying.ie/return/66639/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:12,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Trade,Brexit - Export Trade to Northern Ireland,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament::John Callinan|Second Secretary General|Department of the Taoiseach","That live export trade to Northern Ireland for slaughter cattle would continue unfettered access to the UK market, regardless of the outcome of Brexit.::To highlight that the Northern Ireland market provides vital competition for Irish beef farmers with finished cattle and has performed very strongly this year.",|Email|1::|Virtual Meeting|2-5::|Informal communication|2-5,Tim Cullinan IFA President,No,,False,,False,
66640,lobbying.ie/return/66640/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:11,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Climate Measures,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament","To highlight that sales of protected urea have increased significantly this year. From January to June, just under 40000 tonnes were sold, compared to 21,000 in 2019.::To highlight that according to Teagasc, protected urea is the number one technology to reduce losses of both ammonia (from urea) and the Green house Gas (GHG) nitrous oxide into the atmosphere.::To highlight that farmers have also continued to invest in Low Emmission Slurry Spreading Equipment (LESS). With the grant support from TAMS, farmers have already invested as estimated €79.6m in LESS equipment such as trailing shoes and dribble bars.::To highlight that switching to protected urea and using LESS equipment are two of the main actions at farm level identiied by the Teagasc MACC to reduce green-house gas and ammonia emissions.",|Email|1,"Tom Phelan IFA Dairy Chair, Paul O'Brien IFA Environment Chair",No,,False,,False,
66641,lobbying.ie/return/66641/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:11,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Ireland's Forestry Sector - State of Emergency,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament::Pippa Hackett|Super Junior Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine","IFA Proposes the following six emergency measures:::1.The system must ensure that no farmer has to wait longer than four months for a forestry licence as set out in the Forestry Act 2014 Section 18 (1), irrespective of the application size.::2. Forest road and felling/thinning licence applications that are in the system for more than this period (four months) should be automatically approved under an amnesty provision::3. Amend the Forestry Act 2014 to introduce exemptions for forest road and thinning operations, these do not present a significant landscape change and present a low risk from an environmental perspective::4. Review the current appropriate assessment (AA) screening process, associated rules and thresholds. In particular, introduce a threshold that forests less than 15 hectares should be exempt from the AA screening requirement. Only Forests over 15 hectares would be screened to determine if they need to submit a Natura Impact Statement (NIS) while forests over 50 hectares must submit a full Environmental Impact Assessment (EIA) as is currently the situation.::5. A cost-based planning support grant should be introduced, as referenced in the Mackinnon report, to assist with increased costs and requirements associated with applying for licenses::6. The appointment of an independent Project Manager within the Department to implement the operational changes recommended in the Mackinnon report to develop an appropriate and effective licensing system.",|Email|2-5::|Social Media|2-5,"Tim Cullinan IFA President, Vincent Nally IFA Farm Forestry Sector",No,,False,,False,
66642,lobbying.ie/return/66642/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:10,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,Agricultural Appeals (Amendment ) Bill 2020   /  Forestry (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2020,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament",To highlight that the Cabinet decision to amend the Agricultural Appeals Act must deliver efficiency in the forestry appeals system that makes it fit for purpose::To ensure that farmers have confidence in the system and that their appeals will be heard within a defined timeframe so they can manage their forest sustainably::To highlight that there are over a million cubic meters of wood caught up in the backlog,|Email|1,Vincent Nally IFA Farm Forestry Chair,No,,False,,False,
66643,lobbying.ie/return/66643/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,20/01/2021 22:10,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Matters involving public funds,Agriculture,Basic Payment Scheme (BPS) & Other Farm Schemes Payout 2020,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Dillon|Assistant Secretary|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament",That there would be maximium payout of the 2020 farm schemes given the difficulties from COVID-19 restrictions::That 70% of the BPS would be paid out on October 16th,|Email|2-5::|Phone call|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|1,Brian Rushe IFA Deputy President  & Michael Biggins IFA Rural Development Chairman,No,,False,,False,
66644,lobbying.ie/return/66644/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,20/01/2021 22:13,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Matters involving public funds,Agriculture,Charter of Farmers' Rights,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament",To ensure that the maximum number of applicants in Tranch 19 of TAMS (Targetted Agricultural Measures) are approved as soon as possible to provide certainty to farmers who are planning to carry out work.::To welcome conformation that the ANC (Areas of Natural Constraint) payment would come shortly and to stree the importance of paying the remaining farmers as soon as they meet their stocking density requirements::That the Department pay the ANC payment to farmers who omitted in error to tick the ANC box in their Basic Payment application this year.::To welcome the Department of Agriculture facilitation of farmers who made 'Draft applications' to BEEP-S scheme and who had operated under the impression that they were participating in the scheme by carrying out measures on their farms.::That the Beef Finishers Payment would be paid on vattle exported for slaughter in the reference period from the surplus in the Beef Finishers Payment Fund.,|Email|1,"Brian Rushe IFA Deputy President, Michael Biggins IFA Rural Development Chair, Brendan Golden IFA Livestock Chair",No,,False,,False,
66645,lobbying.ie/return/66645/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:09,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Environment,EU Strategy to Reduce Methane Emissions,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament","That it was correct that the EU would set up an expert group in the first half of 2021 to analyse the life cycle of methane emissions::To highlight that the science was evolving. Research by Oxford University led by Myles Allen has demonstrated how the current methodology used to calculate methane emissions is not appropriate and that this needs to be reflected in how inventories are developed.::That the emphasis must be on reducing emissions per animal rather than on herd reduction. The commitment to develop a carbon navigator template to calculate carbon emissions and removals, acknowledges the carbon farmers are removing from the atmosphere, not just the emissions.::To stress that farmers in the EU are getting no credit for the carbon they currently sequester through tehir pasture, crops and hedgerows",|Email|1,Paul O'Brien IFA Environment Chair,No,,False,,False,
66646,lobbying.ie/return/66646/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,21/01/2021 14:08,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Environment,Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) Licensing of Dairy Farms,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament::James O'Connor|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine",That IFA rejects any proposal to have EPA licening of dairy farms::That any such move would be over the top and disproportionate::To highlight that dairy farmers are already heavily regulated with cross-compliance and the nitrates derogation. Farmers are also participating in voluntary programmes such as ASSAP and the Agricultural Catchments Programme to improve water quality in slected catchments.,|Email|2-5::|Informal communication|2-5::|Virtual Meeting|1,"Tim Cullinan IFA President, Tom Phelan IFA Dairy Chair",No,,False,,False,
66647,lobbying.ie/return/66647/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,20/01/2021 22:40,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Energy and Natural Resources,Public Service Obligation (PSO) Levy,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament",That a percentage of the PSO levy must be set aside for community-owned renewable projects::To highlight the benefits from community-based renewable energy projects. They provide sustainability greater economic benefits and job creation within the community and reduce the concentration of economic power of commercial utilities in the electricity business.,|Email|1,Paul O'Brien IFA Environment Chair,No,,False,,False,
66648,lobbying.ie/return/66648/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,20/01/2021 22:39,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,TB Forum,"Charlie McConalogue|Minister|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Martin Heydon|Minister of State|Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament","To welcome the contribution of the Minister for Agriculture to the TB Forum and the direction to his officials to provide the Forum members with a draft TB strategy and to initiate bi-lateral meetings with the farm organisations in particular as a matter of urgency, to develop an agreed approach in achieving the eradication of TB in the shortest feasible timeframe.::That the letters and subsequent correspondence with farmers must be stopped immediately and a comprehensive programme to eradicate TB developed in agreement with farmers on the three ket areas of Wildlife Control; on-farm investigation of disease outbreaks; and financial supports for farms under TB controls.",|Email|1,Pat Farrell IFA Animal Health Chair,No,,False,,False,
66649,lobbying.ie/return/66649/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,20/01/2021 22:39,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Agriculture,The Farming Sector in Ireland: A Profile from Revenue Data - Office of the Revenue Commissioners,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament","To highlight that this report by the Revenue Commissioners demonstrates the struggle of generational renewal. That 37% of farmers are aged over 60, while only 24% of farmers are under 40.",|Email|1,Rose Mary McDonagh IFA Farm Business Chair,No,,False,,False,
66650,lobbying.ie/return/66650/the-irish-farmers-association---ifa,The Irish Farmers' Association - IFA,20/01/2021 22:37,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,EU Affairs,EU Veterinary Medicine Regulation,"Jackie Cahill|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Martin Browne|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Matt Carthy|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Collins|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Fitzmaurice|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Joe Flaherty|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Paul Kehoe|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Brian Leddin|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Michael Ring|TD|Dáil Éireann, the Oireachtas::Victor Boyhan|Senator|Seanad::Lynn Boylan|Senator|Seanad::Paul Daly|Senator|Seanad::Tim Lombard|Senator|Seanad::Denis O'Donovan|Senator|Seanad::Chris MacManus|MEP|European Parliament::Deirdre Clune|MEP|European Parliament::Barry Andrews|MEP|European Parliament::Luke Ming Flanagan|MEP|European Parliament::Seán Kelly|MEP|European Parliament::Frances Fitzgerald|MEP|European Parliament::Clare Daly|MEP|European Parliament::Mick Wallace|MEP|European Parliament::Billy Kelleher|MEP|European Parliament::Maria Walsh|MEP|European Parliament::Ciarán Cuffe|MEP|European Parliament::Grace O'Sullivan|MEP|European Parliament::Colm Markey|MEP|European Parliament",To highlight that the new EU Veterinary Medicine Regulation has the potential to severely impact on competition in the supply of anthelmintics to farmers::To highlight that the regulation also threatens the future viability of Licensed Merchant stores and veterinary pharmacies if the Department of Agriculture doesnt resolve the issue,|Email|1,Pat Farrell IFA Animal Health Chair,No,,False,,False,
