67993,lobbying.ie/return/67993/an-taisce-the-national-trust-for-ireland,An Taisce The National Trust for Ireland,20/01/2021 16:37,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Energy and Natural Resources,REQUEST FOR REVIEW OF FUNCTION AND OPERATION OF THE STATE COMPANY GAS NETWORKS IRELAND UNDER GAS ACT 1976 (AS AMENDED) IN ADDRESSING THE CLIMATE AND BIODIVERSITY LOSS EMERGENCY,"Eamon Ryan|Minister|Department of Climate Action, Communication Networks and Transport",The legal remit and operations of GNI need to be entirely reconstituted and integrated with coordinated national action on the climate emergency.::Parallel review is also required on the function and operation of the Commissioner for Regulation of Utilities.,|Letter|1,Philip Kearney,No,,False,,False,
67995,lobbying.ie/return/67995/the-wheel,The Wheel,21/01/2021 14:39,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Matters involving public funds,Budgetary matters,"On the 23rd September - we hand delivered copies of our pre-budget submission to - Minister Heather Humphries, DRCD  - Minister of State Joe O Brien, DRCD  - Minister Paschal Donohoe, Finance  - Minister Stephen Donnelly, Health  - Minister Michael McGrath, Public Expenditure and Reform",Heather Humphreys|Minister|Department of Social Protection::Joe O'Brien|Minister of State|Department of Rural and Community Development::Paschal Donohoe|Minister|Department of Finance::Michael McGrath|Minister|Department of Public Expenditure and Reform::Stephen Donnelly|Minister|Department of Health,"The Wheel called on Government to: 1. Provide adequate and sustainable funding for the sector.  2. Streamline regulatory and funding-related compliance requirements and provide for the costs of compliance.  3. Bring down the cost of insurance.  4. Comprehensively resource the new strategies for the community and voluntary sector and social enterprise.  5. Implement the recommendations of the Report of the Independent Review Group  on the Role of Voluntary Providers in Publicly Funded Services::The Wheel called on Government to: 4. Comprehensively resource the new strategies for the community and voluntary sector and social enterprise.  5. Implement the recommendations of the IRG Report. 6. Develop a framework for collaborative working and provide resources and supports for mergers.  7. Increase budget allocations for Department of Rural and Community Development::The introduction of similarly proportional increases to the Community Employment Scheme (CE) and the Rural Social Scheme (RSS), as well as changes to the way the schemes are currently run, including recommendations on: training, reporting requirements, Garda vetting, recruitment and referral practices, IT systems, flexibility around the time and duration of schemes, facilitation of participation of older people in the schemes, uniformity of implementation and financial compensation.","On the 23rd September - we hand delivered copies of our pre-budget submission to - Minister Heather Humphries, DRCD  - Minister of State Joe O Brien, DRCD  - Minister Paschal Donohue, Finance  - Minister Donnelly, Health  - Minister McGrath, Public Expenditure and Reform|Submission|1","Sarah Monaghan, Campaigns Manager and Deirdre Garvey CEO",No,,False,,False,
67996,lobbying.ie/return/67996/irish-congress-of-trade-unions,Irish Congress of Trade Unions,20/01/2021 16:40,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Legislation,Public Expenditure and Reform,Letter sent to Minister regarding Public Procurement and Promoting Collective Bargaining,Michael McGrath|Minister|Department of Public Expenditure and Reform::Ossian Smyth|Minister of State|Department of Public Expenditure and Reform,Letter sent to Minister requesting information and a meeting about Public Procurement and Promoting Collective Bargaining,|Email|1,"Patricia King, General Secretary ICTU",No,,False,,False,
67997,lobbying.ie/return/67997/macra-na-feirme,Macra na Feirme,21/01/2021 17:45,"1 Sep, 2020 to 31 Dec, 2020",Public policy or programme,Trade,Discussion on Brexit and Irish agri-food trade with Minister Conveney,Simon Coveney|Minister|Department of Foreign Affairs,"Support for young farmers should there be a major impact on farm gate prices as a result of a No-Deal Brexit which is beyond their control, to ensure that young farmers can afford to make repayments on investments made::To ensure that cross border trade is protected for young farmers in the border countries::To secure markets for all Irish products in other countries if the UK market is lost::To ensure that there is no impact on the processing of milk and meat products on the island of Ireland",|Email|1::16 November via Zoom|Virtual Meeting|1,"Thomas Duffy, National President; Derrie Dillon, Head of Advocacy, Membership & Policy; Shane Fitzgerald, Ag Affairs Chairperson  & Gillian Richardson, Ag Policy Officer",No,,False,,False,
